column16: Number of octets in received packets for this association, including duplicates and those received in error.
column17: An SCTP packet is received.

column16: Number of valid one minute intervals within ROP, delayRTT values is based on.\nIf retransmit occurs in one minute interval, specific interval will be excluded from result.\nIf retransmit occurs in all 15 one minute intervals no delayRTT values will be presented.

Number of outgoing user data messages, which were discarded even though no problems were encountered to prevent their transmission. User messages are discarded due to lack of space in the transmission buffer.
column17: An outgoing user message is discarded.

column16: Minimum Round Trip Time value observed from all valid one minute intervals within ROP
Number of received DATA chunks with errors in the chunk format or in the chunk contents preventing them from being delivered to the SCTP user.
column17: A received chunk is discarded.

column16: Number of received control chunks which were discarded even though no errors were detected. Chunks can be discarded for the following reasons:\n- unsupported chunk type.\n- wrong association state.
column17: A received chunk is discarded.

column16: Number of transmitted control chunks.
column17: A control chunk is transmitted.

column16: Number of received control chunks which were chosen to be discarded due to errors in the chunk format or in the chunk content.
column17: A received chunk is discarded.

column16: Number of outgoing DATA chunks for this association for which no problems were encountered to prevent their transmission but were discarded. DATA chunks are discarded due to ungraceful closing of the association.
column17: An outgoing DATA chunk is discarded.

column16: Number of retransmitted DATA chunks.
column17: A DATA chunk is retransmitted.

column16: Number of octets in transmitted packets.
column17: An SCTP packet is transmitted.

column16: Number of received control chunks.\n\nThe counter does not include abnormal or discarded chunks.
column17: A control chunk is received.

column16: Number of seconds that the local transmission buffer for the association is congested.
column17: The accumulated association congestion time reaches 1 second.

column16: Number of times that the association has become unavailable to the SCTP user due to ungraceful termination by the local or the remote side, using the chunk ABORT.Ungraceful termination during association establishment does not increment this counter.
column17: State change from ESTABLISHED to CLOSED, during ABORT.

column16: Number of times that the association has become unavailable to the SCTP user due to graceful shutdown by the local or the remote side.
column17: State change from SHUTDOWN-SENT or SHUTDOWN-ACK-SENT directly to CLOSED.

column16: Number of received DATA chunks.\n\nThe counter does NOT include abnormal or discarded chunks.
column17: A DATA chunk is received.

column16: Number of transmitted packets.
column17: An SCTP packet is transmitted.

column16: Number of times that the local transmission buffer for the association is congested.
column17: The association becomes congested.

column16: Maximum Round Trip Time value observed from all valid one minute intervals within ROP.
Number of received DATA chunks that were discarded due to lack of space in the receive buffer.
column17: A received chunk is discarded.

column16: Number of times that the association has started the zero window supervision procedure.
column17: The association starts the zero window supervision procedure.

column16: Average Round Trip Time value from all valid one minute intervals within ROP.
Number of transmitted DATA chunks (excluding retransmissions).
column17: A DATA chunk is transmitted.

column16:
Number of times that the association has become unavailable to the SCTP user because all paths forming part of this association became inactive for one of the following reasons:

- Retransmission limit was reached
- an ICMP message is received and is treated as if the retransmission limit was reached
column17: State change from any state directly to CLOSED after the maximum number of retransmissions is reached, or if an ICMP message is received and breaks the retransmission counter.

column16: Number of seconds the association has been unavailable to the SCTP user.\n\nUnit: 1 s
column17: The accumulated time in DISABLED operational state reaches one second.

column16: Number of seconds that the remote peer has claimed to have zero window for its receive buffer.
column17: The accumulated time the association has spent on zero window supervision reaches one second.

column16: Number of received packets for this association, including duplicates and those received in error.
column17: An SCTP packet is received.

column16: The total number of broadcast packets that are requested to be transmitted. Broadcast packets counted by ifOutDiscards and ifOutErrors are included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The total number of unicast packets that are requested to be transmitted. Unicast packets counted by ifOutDiscards and ifOutErrors are included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The number of outbound packets that could not be transmitted because of errors. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.

The number of unicast packets  forwarded to a bridge or delivered to a higher (sub-)layer. Packets counted by ifInErrors, ifInUnknownProtos, ifInUnknownTags and ifInDiscards are not included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The number of inbound packets that contained errors preventing them from being deliverable to a higher-layer protocol. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.

The number of broadcast packets forwarded to a bridge or delivered to a higher (sub-)layer. Packets counted by ifInErrors, ifInUnknownProtos, ifInUnknownTags and ifInDiscards are not included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The number of outbound packets which were discarded even though no errors had been detected, for example due to lack of buffer space or traffic shaping. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The number of packets received via the interface which were discarded because of an unknown VLAN ID.

Distribution of the ingress throughput on the ethernet interface measured in octets per second. The throughput samples are based on ifHCInOctets and are taken every second. This counter is not supported for EthernetPort MO when using IDL port.
column17: Each bin is calculated as a percentile value at the end of the ROP period. 7 percentile values are presented in the bins [0,1,...,6] = [P0, P95, P96, P97, P98, P99, P100].

column16: The number of multicast packets forwarded to a bridge or delivered to a higher (sub-)layer. Packets counted by ifInErrors, ifInUnknownProtos, ifInUnknownTags and ifInDiscards are not included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The total number of octets transmitted out of the interface, including framing characters. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The total number of octets received on the interface, including framing characters.Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The number of packets received via the interface which were discarded because of an unknown or unsupported protocol. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
Total duration in milliseconds where connection is lost due to Ethernet link failures, measured via the loss of signal detection.

The number of inbound packets which were chosen to be discarded even though no errors had been detected to prevent their being deliverable to a higher-layer protocol. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The total number of multicast packets that are requested to be transmitted. Multicast packets counted by ifOutDiscards and ifOutErrors are included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
Maximum duration in milliseconds where connection is lost due to Ethernet link failures, measured via the loss of signal detection.
The total number of times connection is lost due to Ethernet link failures, measured via the loss of signal detection.

Distribution of the egress throughput on the ethernet interface measured in octets per second. The throughput samples are based on ifHCOutOctets and are taken every second. This counter is not supported for EthernetPort MO when using IDL port.
column17: Each bin is calculated as a percentile value at the end of the ROP period. 7 percentile values are presented in the bins [0,1,...,6] = [P0, P95, P96, P97, P98, P99, P100].

column16: Minimum duration in milliseconds where connection is lost due to Ethernet link failures, measured via the loss of signal detection.

column10: Contains all PM counters for EDchResourcesCell
column16: Sum of sample values recorded during ROP for number of Serving E-DCH users.
column17: New sampled value is added each second of the granuality period. Measurement starts when EUL resources are setup.

column10: Contains all PM counters for EDchResourcesCell
column16: Number of samples in pmSumCapacityServEDchUsers.\npmSamplesCapacityServEDchUsers = pmSamplesCapacityServEDchUsers + 1, whenever pmSumCapacityServEDchUsers is updated.
column17: Stepped each time a measurement value is sampled for pmSumCapacityServEDchUsers. Measurement starts when EUL resources are setup.

column10: Contains all PM counters for EDchResourcesCell
column16:
Total DL power used for the E-AGCH, E-RGCH and E-HICH in the cell.

Bins:
[0]: Number of samples in range [0..1[ dBm
[1]: Number of samples in range [1..2[ dBm
...
[39]: Number of samples in range [39..40[ dBm
[40]: Number of samples greater than or equal to 40 dBm
column17: Sample every 100 ms is an average over 100 ms. \n      Measurement starts when EUL resources are setup. Counter is not stepped because of EUL FACH activity.\n

column10: Contains all PM counters for EDchResourcesCell
column16: Number of rejected attempts to allocate resources for new Serving E-DCH user (related to pmCapacityLimitServEDchUser).
column17: Sample taken each granularity period. Measurement starts when EUL resources are setup.

column10: Contains all PM counters for EDchResourcesCell
column16:
Distribution of number of Serving E-DCH users, as percentages of licensed limit visible in pmCapacityLimitServEDchUsers.
Bins:
[0]: Number of sampled values in range [0..20[ %
[1]: Number of sampled values in range [20..40[ %
[2]: Number of sampled values in range [40..50[ %
[3]: Number of sampled values in range [50..60[ %
[4]: Number of sampled values in range [60..70[ %
[5]: Number of sampled values in range [70..80[ %
[6]: Number of sampled values in range [80..85[ %
[7]: Number of sampled values in range [85..90[ %
[8]: Number of sampled values in range [90..95[ %
[9]: Number of sampled values >= 95%
column17: Sampled each second of the granularity period which gives 900 values. Measurement starts when EUL resources are setup. Counter is not stepped due to EUL FACH activity.

column10: Contains all PM counters for EDchResourcesCell
column16: Number of rejected attempts to allocate E-DCH radio links in EUL scheduler. Includes number of removed E-DCH radio links due EUL user setup, when limit is reached of total number of E-DCH radio links in baseband pool.
column17: Stepped for each rejected allocation attempt.

column10: Contains all PM counters for EDchResourcesCell
column16: Number of attempts to allocate resources for new Serving E-DCH user.\nIf the corresponding carrier is part of a cell using more than one carrier, its value is undefined
column17: Stepped for each allocation attempt. Measurement starts when EUL resources are setup.

column10: Contains all PM counters for EDchResourcesCell
column16: Licensed limit for number of Serving E-DCH users in the cell.\nLicense key value if valid license key, else default value of NodeBLocalCell::maxNumEulUsers if invalid/missing license key, else max value of NodeBLocalCell::maxNumEulUsers if emergency unlock is active.
column17: Sampled when the limit changes.

column16: The number of input IP datagrams discarded because the datagram frame did not carry enough data. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of IP multicast datagrams transmitted. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of locally-addressed IP datagrams received successfully but discarded because of an unknown or unsupported protocol. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of IP datagrams that have been successfully fragmented. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The total number of input IP datagrams received, including those received in error. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The total number of IP datagrams that this entity supplied to the lower layers for transmission. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of failures detected by the IP re-assembly algorithm. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
Distribution of the ingress throughput on the IPv6 interface measured in octets per second.\nThe throughput samples are based on ipIfStatsHCInOctets and are taken every second.
column17: Each bin is calculated as a percentile value at the end of the ROP period. 7 percentile values are presented in the bins [0,1,...,6] = [P0, P95, P96, P97, P98, P99, P100].

column16: The number of output datagram fragments that have been generated as a result of IP fragmentation. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of datagrams for which this entity was not their final IP destination and for which it was successful in finding a path to their final destination. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of input IP datagrams discarded due to errors in  their IP headers, including version number mismatch, other  format errors, hop count exceeded, errors discovered in  processing their IP options, etc. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of output IP datagrams for which no problem was encountered to prevent their transmission to their destination, but were discarded (e.g., for lack of buffer space). Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The total number of octets transmitted in IP multicast datagrams. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of input datagrams for which this entity was not their final IP destination and for which this entity attempted to find a route to forward them to that final destination. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of input IP datagrams for which no problems were  encountered to prevent their continued processing, but were discarded (e.g., for lack of buffer space). ). Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The total number of octets in IP datagrams delivered to the lower layers for transmission. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
Distribution of the egress throughput on the IPv6 interface measured in octets per second.\nThe throughput samples are based on ipIfStatsHCOutOctets and are taken every second.
column17: Each bin is calculated as a percentile value at the end of the ROP period. 7 percentile values are presented in the bins [0,1,...,6] = [P0, P95, P96, P97, P98, P99, P100].

column16: The number of input IP datagrams that are discarded, because no route could be found to transmit them to their destination. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set.  Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of IP fragments received that needed to be reassembled at this interface. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The total number of datagrams successfully delivered to IP user-protocols (including ICMP). Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of IP multicast datagrams received. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The total number of octets received in IP multicast datagrams. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of IP datagrams successfully reassembled. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The total number of octets received in input IP datagrams, including those received in error. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of IP datagrams that have been discarded because they needed to be fragmented but could not be. This includes IPv6 packets that are being forwarded and exceed the outgoing link MTU. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of input IP datagrams discarded because the IP address in their IP header's destination field was not a valid address to be received at this entity. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The total number of IP datagrams that local IP user-protocols (including ICMP) supplied to IP in requests for transmission. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of packets that were forwarded to a null route. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set.

The number of IP datagrams that would require fragmentation in order to be transmitted. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of input IP datagrams discarded because the IP address in their IP header's source field was not a valid address to be received at this entity. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set.

column16: Number of RIM association setup retries.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: A setup retry for a RIM association is initiated.

column16: Number of updates received for a RIM association.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: S1 eNodeB Direct Information Transfer message containing RAN-INFORMATION-PDU or Multiple Report is received.

column16: Number of removed RIM associations.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: RIM association is stopped by the serving RNC, BSS or RIM association is ended by the eNodeB.

column16: Number of successful responses received to set up a RIM association.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: RAN Information Multiple Report or initial message with no error container is received.

column16:
Average voltage in 6 second periods. Sums up voltage of all consumer units having an EnergyMeter.

Deprecated: Since 17.Q3. Has no functional behaviour. Planned to be removed.
column17: Measurement with integration time 6 s, every 6 seconds.

column16: Sum of accumulated energy consumption from start for all consumer units with an EnergyMeter.
column17: Measured regardless of battery charge or discharge.\nIf ROP is incomplete the energy consumption is still accumulated.\n

column16: Average power consumption in 6 second periods.\nSums up power consumption of all consumer units having an EnergyMeter.\n
column17: Measurement with integration time 6 s, every 6 seconds.

column16: Energy consumed during each ROP.\nSums up energy consumption of all consumer units having an EnergyMeter.\n
column17: Measured regardless of battery charge or discharge.

column16: The highest delay round-trip delay in the link between the two ports. Unit: 1 ns. Only valid for C1 (CPRI) link.
column17: This counter reports the highest delay sampled in the granularity period for the link between the units (that is, Baseband-Radio, Radio-Radio). This counter is reported per connection (that is, in a cascaded CPRI configuration). All components such as SFP and FPGA for the link are included in the calculation. A sample is taken every 60 seconds

column16: The lowest delay round-trip delay in the link between the two ports. Unit: 1 ns. Only valid for C1 (CPRI) link.
column17: This counter reports the lowest delay sampled in the granularity period for the link between the units (that is, Baseband-Radio, Radio-Radio). This counter is reported per connection (that is, in a cascaded CPRI configuration). All components such as SFP and FPGA for the link are included in the calculation. A sample is taken every 60 seconds

column16: The total number of L1 reset requests on the link.
column17: Incremented for each L1 reset request from a client. A reset of the radio control link does not increment the counter. Recorded events are accumulated every 60 seconds.

column16: The total number of link stability related errors on the link.
column17: Number of detected stability related errors are accumulated within the granularity period. This can include errors which did not result in an alarm being raised. Recorded events are accumulated every 60 seconds.

column16: The number of attempts to start Single Radio Voice Call Continuity (SRVCC) handover preparation from LTE to CDMA 1xRtt Radio Access Network.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: A better CDMA 1xRtt cell is reported by the UE and a VoIP bearer is established.

column16: The number of successful Single Radio Voice Call Continuity (SRVCC) handover preparations from LTE to CDMA 1xRtt Radio Access Network.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: DL S1 CDMA2000 Tunneling message is received by the eNodeB from the MME with a HO status flag that indicates HO Success.

column16: Number of successful handover preparations triggered by CS Fallback\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The S1AP message Downlink S1 CDMA Tunneling is received and the \HO success\" is indicated for enhanced CS fallback."

column16: Number of attempts to start outgoing handover preparation triggered by high priority CS Fallback\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: EnhancedCS Fallback for emergency call has been initiated for the UE and the eNodeB has selected a target cell for handover.

column16: Number of successful handover preparations triggered by high priority CS Fallback\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The S1AP message Downlink S1 CDMA Tunneling is received and the \HO success\" is indicated for enhanced CS fallback for emergency call."

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

[1]: - 5 less than or equals to delta RSRP_xx less than or equals to - 4
[2]: - 3 less than or equals to delta RSRP_xx less than or equals to - 2
[3]: - 1 less than or equals to delta RSRP_xx less than or equals to - 1
[4]: 0 less than or equals to delta RSRP_xx less than or equals to 0

[7]: 3 less than or equals to delta RSRP_xx less than or equals to 3

[9]: 5 less than or equals to delta RSRP_xx less than or equals to 6

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG and ENDC are not applicable.
Unit: kilobit (1 000 bits)
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Filtered number of cancelled executions of SRVCC handover to UTRAN. Cancelled by RBS.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter QCI, ARP, LCG and CE level are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16: Number of successful handovers to UTRAN or TD-SCDMA. Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.Filter parameters LCG, QCI, ARP and CE_LEVEL not applicable.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
The total number of unsuccessful HARQ transmissions in the downlink direction where a dSINR from DL CoMP was applied in the Link Adaptation.

When carrier aggregation is used, only HARQ transmissions on the UE's primary component carrier (PCell) are counted.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameters QCI, ARP, LCG , CE Level, and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Total number of E-RAB releases initiated by the MME (for each cell) and that there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active).

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Filtered volume (PDCP SDU) that has been transferred on DRB of CA UE in DL in the last TTI when buffer is emptied.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter QCI, ARP, LCG and CE Level are not applicable.
Unit: kilobit (1 000 bits)
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16: Number of attempts to start SRVCC handover execution from LTE to GERAN. Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameters LCG, QCI, ARP and CE_LEVEL not applicable.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Total number of DRB packets (PDCP SDUs) received in the UL.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16: Number of successful SRVCC handover to UTRAN preparations. Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter UE Power Class, subscriber group, and ENDC are applicable.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

Filter parameters UE Power Class, PLMN, UE category, SPID, subscriber group, CE Level, and ENDC are applicable.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Total DL PDCP SDU volume that is transmitted in the last TTI when buffer for DRB is emptied.

When CA is used, PDCP SDU can be sent over multiple cells (PCell/SCell(s)). Total DL PDCP SDU volume is measured on PCell.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG is not applicable.
Unit: kilobit (1 000 bits)
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16: Number of successful handover to UTRAN or TD-SCDMA preparations.\nDifferentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter UE Power Class, subscriber group, and ENDC are applicable.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
The total number of successful RLC PDU transmissions (ACKs) in the uplink direction.

When carrier aggregation is used, only RLC PDU transmissions on the UE's primary component carrier (PCell) are counted.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameters QCI, ARP, LCG, and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Number of DRB packets (PDCP SDUs) successfully transmitted (RLC acknowledged by UE) in the downlink.

When carrier aggregation is used, a PDCP SDU can be sent over multiple cells (PCell/SCell(s)). Total number of DRB packets (PDCP SDUs) successfully transmitted (RLC acknowledged by UE) in the downlink is measured on PCell.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO

column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:

When carrier aggregation is used, a PDCP SDU can be sent over multiple cells (PCell/SCell(s)). Total number of DRB packets (PDCP SDUs) received by eNB in PDCP in DL is measured on PCell.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Total number of UE context releases initiated by the MME excluding successful handover. The counter is stepped regardless of whether data was or was not lost in UL/DL buffers.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter QCI, ARP, LCG, and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
The total number of unsuccessful RLC PDU and RLC PDU segment transmissions (NACKs) in the downlink direction.

When carrier aggregation is used, only RLC PDU transmissions on the UE's primary component carrier (PCell) are counted.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameters QCI, ARP, LCG, and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Total number of abnormal E-RAB releases per cell, initiated by eNodeB due to preemption with precondition of successfully completed Initial Context Establishment procedure and when data was present in UL/DL buffers (i.e. active).

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG is not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Filtered UL DRB volume used for UL CA UE Throughput. It is comprised of MAC SDU volume received on Uu, excluding volume received in the first 4 data receptions of UL buffer transfer and TTI emptying UL buffer.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameters QCI, ARP, LCG and CE Level are not applicable.
Unit: kilobit (1 000 bits)
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16: Number of SRVCC handover preparation attempts from LTE to GSM/EDGE Radio Access Network (GERAN). Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter UE Power Class, subscriber group, and ENDC are applicable.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
The total number of occasions when a downlink HARQ feedback for a transport block using 256QAM modulation was not received from an UE and DTX is considered the reason.

When carrier aggregation is used, only DTX on the UE's primary component carrier (PCell) is counted.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameters QCI, ARP, LCG, CE Level, and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Filtered UL volume transfer time used for UL CA UE Throughput. It is comprised of time periods from when the 5th MAC SDU data reception of UL buffer transfer on Uu until buffer is emptied, excluding TTI emptying buffer.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameters QCI, ARP, LCG and CE Level are not applicable.
Unit: ms
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
The total number of unsuccessful HARQ transmissions in the uplink direction using a QPSK modulation.

When carrier aggregation is used, only HARQ transmissions on the UE's primary component carrier (PCell) are counted.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameters QCI, ARP, LCG, and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Number of DRB packets (PDCP SDUs) forwarded to target cell at handover for DL sessions.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameters LCG, ARP, QCI, and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16: Number of successful outgoing intra-LTE intra-frequency handover preparations. Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameters UE Power Class, subscriber group, UE category, CE Level, and ENDC are applicable.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Total number of abnormal E-RAB releases per cell, initiated by RBS due to UE preemption with precondition of successfully completed Initial Context Establishment procedure. Stepped regardless of UL/DL buffer data loss.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Number of normal E-RAB Releases per cell initiated by eNB.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG is not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Total number of DRB packets (PDCP SDUs) for which no part has been transmitted in DL that are discarded due to reasons other than handover or active queue management.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG and ENDC are not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Number of E-RAB Releases per cell initiated by MME excluding successful handover. Counter is stepped regardless of whether data was or was not lost in UL/DL buffers.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameter LCG is not applicable.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:
Number of DRB packets (PDCP SDUs) discarded in DL due to that the specific tunnel endpoint identifier (TEID) is not mapped to any UE context.

Differentiated by filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter. Filter parameters LCG, ARP, and QCI are not applicable.

Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column16:

Unit: ms
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when matching with filter parameters in MO PmFlexCounterFilter.

column10: Contains all PM counters for IubDataStreams
column16:
Presents a histogram over the dynamic delay experienced between SRNC and RBS by the flow controlled HSDPA flows, that is, the buffer build-up delay distribution for HS traffic on priority class 07.

Bins:
[0]: Number of samples in range [0..10[ ms
[1]: Number of samples in range [10..20[ ms
[2]: Number of samples in range [20..30[ ms
...
[14]: Number of samples in range [140..150[ ms
[15]: Number of samples greater than or equal to 150 ms
column17: The samples are taken from all the HS-DSCH channels scheduled on priority class 07. HS-FACH is not applicable to this counter and HS-FACH transmissions do consequently not trigger the stepping of this counter. This counter is not updated if the AQM feature is activated.

column10: Contains all PM counters for IubDataStreams
column16: Counts all correctly received HS-DSCH data frames in RBS for priority class 05.
column17: This PM counter is valid for priority class 05, regardless if the HS flow is flow controlled or AQM based congestion controlled. One correctly received HS-DSCH data frame increments the counter with one. HS-FACH does not trigger the stepping of this counter.

column10: Contains all PM counters for IubDataStreams
column16:
Degree that HSDPA traffic in DL for SPI 03 is limited by Iub/Iur interfaces, between SRNC and RBS.

Ratio between number of occurrences, when capacity allocation figures are limited by the Iub high-speed bandwidth and number of active flows. Measured every 100 ms.
Unit: 1%
column17:
The PM counter is valid for the flow controlled HSDPA flows only.
The delay is between SRNC and RBS, that is, both Iub and Iur are included in the delay measurement.
HS-FACH transmissions do not step this counter.
This counter is not updated if the AQM feature is activated.

column17: Frame losses are detected by gaps in the FSN. E.g. if frame number (FSN) 13, 14, 15 and 1 are lost in a sequence (discovered by the correctly received data frame with FSN=2), the counter is stepped with 4. FSN=0 is not used when the FSN IE is 'active' in the HS-DSCH data frame structure. The counter is updated regardless of the AQM feature is used or not. The number of lost frames are counted each 100 ms and the resulting value is added to the corresponding PDF bin.

column10: Contains all PM counters for IubDataStreams
column16: The number of Iub DCH Frame Protocol frames received out-of-sequence in the downlink direction.\n
column17: The counter is stepped when an out-of-sequence DCH frame protocol frame is received. A frame is considered to be out-of-sequence if frame_n (or less) arrives after frame_n+1. Since the sequence number is based on Connection Fame Number (CFN) with a range of 0..255, CFN counter wrapping is also taken into account. A frame that is up to 127 numbers later is considered later than the last frame, while a frame that is more than 128 numbers later is considered earlier than the last frame.

column10: Contains all PM counters for IubDataStreams
column16:
Indicates in what degree the EUL traffic in uplink is limited by the Iub/Iur interfaces, between RBS and SRNC. When a high value is indicated, it should be considered to extend Iub/Iur with higher EUL bandwidth.

Indicates the percentage of 100 ms periods with scheduled EUL traffic where Iub has been the only limiting factor during at least one TTI.
Unit: 0.1%
column17:
Measurement is started when EUL resources are setup.

The E-DCH scheduler is limited by:
1) RBS HW,
2) Iub bandwidth, and
3) Uu interface resources.

Resource limitations are measured every 100 ms. Marked as an Iub limiting period if:
- EUL bit rate, edchGrantRate during any 2 and/or 10 ms TTIs during that 100 ms period is higher than available resources, and
- the only limiting resource during one TTIs is E-DCH Iub scheduler limit rate, edchIubSchLimitRate.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
The reason why it is not possible to schedule another high-speed user.
Bins:
[0]: HS-SCCH code shortage
[1]: HS-PDSCH code shortage
[2]: HS-PDSCH power shortage
column17: There are three resources needed for HSDPA user transmission: HS-SCCH codes, HS-PDSCH codes and HS-PDSCH power. These are recorded in separate counter entries. For every subframe and after every scheduled user the Remaining Resource Check function is activated. The counter monitors the function and therefore only steps in active subframes. When it is not possible to schedule another user in the subframe because of resource shortage the counter records the first found reason. As soon as one resource is found short checking stops, thus only one resource counter entry can be incremented per subframe. The function checks the resources in order of counter entry index starting with the lowest. Note that the counter steps even in case there are no more users valid for transmission in current subframe, that is, even if no user that could have used the resources. Resource shortage is considered for both CELL_DCH and HS-FACH users. A HS-FACH user is a UE which is in RRC state CELL_FACH (on RNC level) and is using transport channel HS-DSCH and not FACH. The counter reflects the cell perspective. The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup.

column16:
Distribution over number of multiplexed UE units for each 2ms TTI, of total amount of acknowledged data sent on MAC-hs or MAC-ehs level to UE units configured to use cell, under resource limited conditions.
Scheduling decision is defined to be resource-limited if transport block size is limited only by available codes or power, or both. In addition, condition is not fulfilled if any retransmissions or transmissions to UE units configured in MIMO or HS-FACH mode occur among multiplexed UE units.

Ranges:
[0] : Sum of acknowledged data sent in 2ms TTIs with 2 multiplexed UE units
[1] : Sum of acknowledged data sent in 2ms TTIs with 3 multiplexed UE units
[2] : Sum of acknowledged data sent in 2ms TTIs with 4 multiplexed UE units
column17: Sampled each granularity period. Transmissions for UE units configured in MIMO mode or HS-FACH mode do not step of this counter. Measurement starts when HS-DSCH resources are set up.

    [2]: Number of sampled values in range [1..2[ dBm
    ...
    [50]: Number of sampled values in range [49..50[ dBm
    [51]: Number of sampled values greater than or equal to 50 dBm

Measured for all codes excluding those used for HS-PDSCH, HS-SCCH, E-AGCH, E-RGCH and E-HICH

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
The distribution of the average user rate among all users allocated to high-speed DSCH in the cell. The counter reports the acknowledged throughput for each Priority Queue (PQ) allocated to the cell. For an MC-PQ only the counter in the serving HS-DSCH cell (of the UE to which the MC PQ belongs) is updated. However, the aggregated measurement, based on all cells where the MC-PQ may be served, is considered when that counter is updated. The counter reflects the PQ perspective.
Bins:
[0]: Number of value samples = 0 (no data sent)
[1]: Number of value samples in range ]0..8[ kbps
[2]: Number of value samples in range [8..16[ kbps
[3]: Number of value samples in range [16..32[ kbps
[4]: Number of value samples in range [32..48[ kbps
[5]: Number of value samples in range [48..64[ kbps
[6]: Number of value samples in range [64..96[ kbps
[7]: Number of value samples in range [96..128[ kbps
[8]: Number of value samples in range [128..192[ kbps
[9]: Number of value samples in range [192..256[ kbps
[10]: Number of value samples in range [256..384[ kbps
[11]: Number of value samples in range [384..512[ kbps
[12]: Number of value samples in range [512..768[ kbps
[13]: Number of value samples in range [768..1024[ kbps
[14]: Number of value samples in range [1024..2048[ kbps
[15]: Number of value samples in range [2048..3072[ kbps
[16]: Number of value samples in range [3072..4096[ kbps
[17]: Number of value samples in range [4096..7000[ kbps
[18]: Number of value samples in range [7000..10000[ kbps
[19]: Number of value samples in range [10000..14000[ kbps
[20]: Number of value samples in range [14000..21000[ kbps
[21]: Number of value samples in range [21000..28000[ kbps
[22]: Number of value samples in range [28000..40000[ kbps
[23]: Number of value samples in range [40000..60000[ kbps
[24]: Number of value samples in range [60000..80000[ kbps
[25]: Number of value samples in range [80000..100000[ kbps
[26]: Number of value samples in range [100000..130000[ kbps
[27]: Number of value samples greater than or equal to 130000 kbps
column17:
The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup.
For each PQ, the average user rate is calculated as the ratio
(All transmitted data that is acknowledged)/(Total time the PQ has had data in the buffer).

One measurement sample is taken per call - not per time unit. If a call lasts more than an hour, each full hour will be regarded as a separate call, as will the final partial hour. The result is a statistical distribution of user rates per call during the measurement period.

Packet Switched (PS) Radio Access Bearer (RAB) establishment/release is what defines the start and end of a call.

The average user rate for a particular PQ is calculated according to the formula above, when any of the following occurs:

- A PQ is released.
- A full hour connection time for a user is reached.

The total acknowledged transmitted data and residence time in the buffer must be calculated from measurement start or from the time a call is setup for the first time.

HS-FACH is not applicable to this counter and HS-FACH transmissions do consequently not trigger the stepping of this counter.

      priority classes or going totally empty, then the counter is stepped.

      The counter reflects the cell perspective.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Number of subframes in which no data with scheduling priority class 07 is transmitted
      although there is user data to be sent in the validated PQ. This user data is either waiting for
      first transmission, or data waiting for transmission (NACK is received or no ACK/NACK).
      If a subframe goes without scheduling priority class 07, that is, just carrying other scheduling
      priority classes or going totally empty, then the counter is stepped.
      If the buffer of an MC-PQ is emptied, due to prior scheduling in another cell in the same
      subframe, and no other buffer in the cell contains data the counter is not incremented.
      The counter reflects the cell perspective.
column17: The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup. HS-FACH does not\n      trigger the stepping of this counter. The counter is per cell and per subframe, meaning\n      increments with max 1 per subframe. A \subframe\" is a 2 ms TTI for HS-DSCH."

The counter reflects the cell perspective.

[1]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [1000..2000[ bits
...
[15]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [15000..16000[ bits
[16]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [16000..17000[ bits
[17]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [17000..19000[ bits
[16]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [19000..21000[ bits
...
[28]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [39000..41000[ bits
[29]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [41000..43000[ bits
column17: Increased when ACK is received using 64 QAM, not counting repetitions of ACK transmissions. Counts number of samples in range. HS-FACH is not applicable to this counter and HS-FACH transmissions do consequently not trigger the stepping of this counter. The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup.

column16:
Distribution of HS-PDSCH codes allocated (including HS-PDSCH codes allocated by the RNC).
Values are expressed as percentage of the license controlled level visible in pmCapacityLimitHsPdschCodes. The number of allocated HS-PDSCH code can be reduced below the license limit by non-HS traffic. This means that number of allocated HS-PDSCH codes may not reach 100%. When feature Dynamic Code Allocation is inoperable, HS-PDSCH Codes are only allocated by the RNC.
Bins:
[0]: Number of sampled values in range [0..20[ %
[1]: Number of sampled values in range [20..40[ %
[2]: Number of sampled values in range [40..50[ %
[3]: Number of sampled values in range [50..60[ %
[4]: Number of sampled values in range [60..70[ %
[5]: Number of sampled values in range [70..80[ %
[6]: Number of sampled values in range [80..85[ %
[7]: Number of sampled values in range [85..90[ %
[8]: Number of sampled values in range [90..95[ %
[9]: Number of sampled values >= 95%

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Distribution over CQI, of total number of transmissions to UE units configured to use cell, including retransmissions, on MAC-hs or MAC-ehs level until acknowledgement is received, under resource-limited conditions.
Scheduling decision is defined to be resource-limited if transport block size is limited only by available codes or power, or both. In addition, only one single UE unit must be scheduled for data transmission in 2ms TTI.

CQI value used to index distribution is one reported by UE units and applicable during initial transmission. For non-64QAM-capable UE units, CQI value is mapped down to align with CQI reporting for 64QAM-capable UE units, as further described for PDF range 26...30.

Ranges:
[0] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=0 at initial transmission
[1] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=1 at initial transmission
...
[25] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=25 at initial transmission
[26] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=26 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=26 and 27 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[27] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=27 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=28 and 29 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[28] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=28 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=30 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[29] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=29 at initial transmission for 64QAM-capable UE units (not used for non-64QAM-capable UE units)
[30] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=30 at initial transmission for 64QAM-capable UE units (not used for non-64QAM-capable UE units)
column17: Sampled each granularity period. Transmissions for UE units configured in MIMO mode or HS-FACH mode do not step of this counter. Measurement starts when HS-DSCH resources are set up.

[1]: Number of delays in [10..20[ %
...
[9]: Number of delays in [90..100[ %
[10]: Number of delays greater than or equal to 100%
column17: The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup. HS-FACH does not trigger the stepping of this counter.

[1]: Number of samples in range [0..0.5[ dBm
[2]: Number of samples in range [0.5..1[ dBm
...
[101]: Number of samples in range [50..50.5[ dBm
[102]: Number of samples greater than or equal to 50.5 dBm
column17: Measured every 2 ms for all codes used for transmission of HSDPA channels including HS-PDSCH, HS-SCCH, E-AGCH, E-RGCH and E-HICH. HS-FACH as well as HS traffic on CELL_DCH is part of the measure. The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
The aggregated number of sample values that pmSumScAndMcActUes has been updated with. The following counters are sampled simultaneously and therefore this counter is used to observe how many sample values each counter has been incremented with:
* pmSumScAndMcActUes
* pmSumMcSecActUes
* pmSumMcSecDeactUes
The counter reflects the cell perspective.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Distribution over CQI, of total amount of acknowledged data sent on MAC-hs or MAC-ehs level to UE units configured to use cell.

CQI value used to index distribution is one reported by UE units and applicable during initial transmission. For non-64QAM-capable UE units, CQI value is mapped down to align with CQI reporting for 64QAM-capable UE units, as further described for PDF range 26...30.

Ranges:
[0] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=0 at initial transmission
[1] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=1 at initial transmission
...
[25] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=25 at initial transmission
[26] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=26 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=26 and 27 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[27] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=27 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=28 and 29 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[28] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=28 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=30 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[29] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=29 at initial transmission for 64QAM-capable UE units (not used for non-64QAM-capable UE units)
[30] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=30 at initial transmission for 64QAM-capable UE units (not used for non-64QAM-capable UE units)
column17: Sampled each granularity period. Transmissions for UE units configured in MIMO mode or HS-FACH mode do not step of this counter. Measurement starts when HS-DSCH resources are set up.

column16:
Number of subframes in which no data with scheduling priority class 00 is transmitted
      although there is user data to be sent in the validated PQ. This user data is either waiting for
      first transmission, or data waiting for transmission (NACK is received or no ACK/NACK).
      If a subframe goes without scheduling priority class 00, that is, just carrying other scheduling
      priority classes or going totally empty, then the counter is stepped.
      If the buffer of an MC-PQ is emptied, due to prior scheduling in another cell in the same
      subframe, and no other buffer in the cell contains data the counter is not incremented.
      The counter reflects the cell perspective.
column17: The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup. HS-FACH does not\n      trigger the stepping of this counter. The counter is per cell and per subframe, meaning\n      increments with max 1 per subframe. A \subframe\" is a 2 ms TTI for HS-DSCH."

column16:
Number of subframes in which no data with scheduling priority class 02 is transmitted
      although there is user data to be sent in the validated PQ. This user data is either waiting for
      first transmission, or data waiting for transmission (NACK is received or no ACK/NACK).

      priority classes or going totally empty, then the counter is stepped.

      The counter reflects the cell perspective.
column17: The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup. HS-FACH does not\n      trigger the stepping of this counter. The counter is per cell and per subframe, meaning\n      increments with max 1 per subframe. A \subframe\" is a 2 ms TTI for HS-DSCH."

column16: Number of Iub discards on all Priority Queues (PQs), that experienced the frame loss due to Iub congestion, for Scheduling Priority Indicator (SPI) 11.
column17: The counter is only stepped if AQM feature is ACTIVATED and if SPI 11 is active for the AQM feature (set by IubDataStreams::hsAqmCongCtrlSpiOnOff). When HSDPA RBR QoS Profiling feature is ACTIVATED, then only the discards triggered by Iub congestions where the discards were done on the PQs that also experienced the frame loss are counted, that is, not the discards detected by RBR QoS profiling. When HSDPA RBR QoS Profiling feature is DEACTIVATED, then this counter counts all discards triggered by frame loss (Iub congestion). For discard due to Iub congestion this is done when the discard flag is checked. For MC PQs, the discards shall be counted in the HS-DSCH cell where the discard was performed.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Distribution over CQI, of total number of transmissions to UE units configured to use cell, including retransmissions, on MAC-hs or MAC-ehs level until acknowledgement is received.

CQI value used to index distribution is one reported by UE units and applicable during initial transmission. For non-64QAM-capable UE units, CQI value is mapped down to align with CQI reporting for 64QAM-capable UE units, as further described for PDF range 26...30.

Ranges:
[0] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=0 at initial transmission
[1] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=1 at initial transmission
...
[25] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=25 at initial transmission
[26] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=26 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=26 and 27 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[27] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=27 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=28 and 29 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[28] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=28 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=30 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[29] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=29 at initial transmission for 64QAM-capable UE units (not used for non-64QAM-capable UE units)
[30] : Number of transmissions for reported CQI=30 at initial transmission for 64QAM-capable UE units (not used for non-64QAM-capable UE units)
column17: Sampled each granularity period. Transmissions for UE units configured in MIMO mode or HS-FACH mode do not step of this counter. Measurement starts when HS-DSCH resources are set up.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Distribution over CQI, of total amount of acknowledged data sent on MAC-hs or MAC-ehs level to UE units configured to use cell, under resource limited conditions.
Scheduling decision is defined to be resource-limited if transport block size is limited only by available codes or power, or both. In addition, only one single UE unit must be scheduled for data transmission in 2ms TTI.

CQI value used to index distribution is one reported by UE units and applicable during initial transmission. For non-64QAM-capable UE units, CQI value is mapped down to align with CQI reporting for 64QAM-capable UE units, as further described for PDF range 26...30.

Ranges:
[0] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=0 at initial transmission
[1] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=1 at initial transmission
...
[25] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=25 at initial transmission
[26] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=26 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=26 and 27 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[27] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=27 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=28 and 29 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[28] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=28 for 64QAM-capable UE units, or reported CQI=30 for non-64QAM-capable UE units, at initial transmission
[29] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=29 at initial transmission for 64QAM-capable UE units (not used for non-64QAM-capable UE units)
[30] : Sum of acknowledged data sent for reported CQI=30 at initial transmission for 64QAM-capable UE units (not used for non-64QAM-capable UE units)
column17: Sampled each granularity period. Transmissions for UE units configured in MIMO mode or HS-FACH mode do not step of this counter. Measurement starts when HS-DSCH resources are set up.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Number of attempts to allocate HS-PDSCH codes.
Attempts to allocate HS-DSCH codes can be done in the following cases:
- When RNC sets up or releases HS-PDSCH codes. If codes are released by the RNC, they might be allocated by RBS dynamically if dynamic code allocation is active.
- Fluctuating R99 traffic with dynamic code allocation active might increase the counter. If increased R99 traffic cause a code collision in the code tree for one cell, then dynamically allocated HS-PDSCH codes are released and used for R99 traffic instead. Later when the R99 traffic is released, then the codes will be dynamically allocated again and thus increase the counter.
column17: Sampled each granularity period. Measurement starts when the HS-DSCH resources are setup.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16: Number of discards performed by the AQM feature for all Priority Queues (PQs) for Scheduling Priority Indicator (SPI) 00.
column17: The counter is only stepped if the AQM feature is activated and if SPI 00 is active for the AQM feature (set by IubDataStreams::hsAqmCongCtrlSpiOnOff). Only discards due to Uu congestion steps the counter. For MC PQs, the discards shall be counted in the HS-DSCH cell where the discard was performed.

column17: The counter is only stepped if AQM feature is ACTIVATED and if SPI 13 is active for the AQM feature (set by IubDataStreams::hsAqmCongCtrlSpiOnOff). When HSDPA RBR QoS Profiling feature is ACTIVATED, then only the discards triggered by Iub congestions where the discards were done on the PQs that also experienced the frame loss are counted, that is, not the discards detected by RBR QoS profiling. When HSDPA RBR QoS Profiling feature is DEACTIVATED, then this counter counts all discards triggered by frame loss (Iub congestion). For discard due to Iub congestion this is done when the discard flag is checked. For MC PQs, the discards shall be counted in the HS-DSCH cell where the discard was performed.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources

Distribution of number of HS-DSCH users, as percentages of the license controlled limit visible in pmCapacityLimitHsDschUsers.
Bins:
[0]: Number of sampled values in range [0..5[ %
[1]: Number of sampled values in range [5..10[ %
...
[18]: Number of sampled values in range [90..95[ %
[19]: Number of sampled values >= 95%
column17: Sampled each second of the granularity period. HS-FACH is not applicable to this counter and HS-FACH transmissions do consequently not trigger the stepping of this counter. Measurement starts when the HS-DSCH resources are setup.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Number of received ACKs for a specified transport block size (TBS) with 16 QAM. The number of successful HARQ transmissions are counted on the MAC-hs layer. The counter does not consider whether or not the transmitted data originates from an MC-PQ. The counter does not consider ACK/NACKs corresponding to HS-SCCH orders. The counter reflects the cell perspective.
Bins:
[0]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [0..1000[ bits
[1]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [1000..2000[ bits
[2]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [2000..3000[ bits
...
[28]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [28000..29000[ bits
[29]: Number of ACKs for transport block with size [29000..30000[ bits
column17: Increased when ACK is received using 16 QAM, not counting repetitions of ACK transmissions. Counts number of samples in range. HS-FACH is not applicable to this counter and HS-FACH transmissions do consequently not trigger the stepping of this counter. The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup. A UE unit in MC mode (with secondary serving HS-DSCH cell or cells activated) reports an independent CQI for each cell in the serving HS-DSCH cell set. The counter in each cell is therefore incremented accordingly. A UE unit in MC mode with deactivated secondary serving HS-DSCH cell or cells reports the CQI only for the serving HS-DSCH cell. Thus, only the counter in the serving HS-DSCH cell is incremented.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Distribution over number of multiplexed UE units for each 2ms TTI, of total amount of transmissions to UE units configured to use cell, including retransmissions, on MAC-hs or MAC-ehs level until acknowledgement is received, under resource-limited conditions.
Scheduling decision is defined to be resource-limited if transport block size is limited only by available codes or power, or both. In addition, condition is not fulfilled if any retransmissions or transmissions to UE units configured in MIMO or HS-FACH mode occur among multiplexed UE units.

Ranges:
[0] : Number of transmissions for data initially scheduled in 2ms TTIs with 2 multiplexed UE units
[1] : Number of transmissions for data initially scheduled in 2ms TTIs with 3 multiplexed UE units
[2] : Number of transmissions for data initially scheduled in 2ms TTIs with 4 multiplexed UE units
column17: Sampled each granularity period. Transmissions for UE units configured in MIMO mode or HS-FACH mode do not step of this counter. Measurement starts when HS-DSCH resources are set up.

column16: Number of PQs with data in the buffer for each 2 ms subframe.\nOnly PQs with scheduling priority class 06 and belonging to UEs units configured to use cell as serving HS-DSCH cell in MC mode are considered. The counter reflects the PQ perspective.
column17: Sampled each granularity period. HS-FACH does not trigger the stepping of this counter. The actual measurement starts when the HS-DSCH resources are set up.

...

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Number of used transport block size (TBS) with QPSK. A transport block is a HARQ data block (MAC-hs PDU). The number of HARQ transmissions and retransmissions on the MAC-hs layer are counted. The counter does not consider whether or not the transmitted data originates from an MC-PQ. The counter reflects the cell perspective.
Bins:
[0]: Number of used transport blocks with size [0..1000[ bits
[1]: Number of used transport blocks with size [1000..2000[ bits
[2]: Number of used transport blocks with size [2000..3000[ bits
...
[29]: Number of used transport blocks with size [29000..30000[ bits
column17: Increased on transmission of a Transport Block using QPSK. Counts number of transport blocks in range. HS-FACH does not trigger the stepping of this counter. The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup.

The discards are done for the PQs with the highest rates when normalized with the corresponding IubDataStreams::hsRbrWeight values. For MC PQs, the discards shall be counted in the HS-DSCH cell where the discard was performed.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16: Number of Iub discards on all Priority Queues (PQs), that experienced the frame loss due to Iub congestion, for Scheduling Priority Indicator (SPI) 12.
column17: The counter is only stepped if AQM feature is ACTIVATED and if SPI 12 is active for the AQM feature (set by IubDataStreams::hsAqmCongCtrlSpiOnOff). When HSDPA RBR QoS Profiling feature is ACTIVATED, then only the discards triggered by Iub congestions where the discards were done on the PQs that also experienced the frame loss are counted, that is, not the discards detected by RBR QoS profiling. When HSDPA RBR QoS Profiling feature is DEACTIVATED, then this counter counts all discards triggered by frame loss (Iub congestion). For discard due to Iub congestion this is done when the discard flag is checked. For MC PQs, the discards shall be counted in the HS-DSCH cell where the discard was performed.

column16:
Total amount of acknowledged data sent on MAC-hs level per scheduling priority class 12.
      The counter does not consider whether or not the transmitted data originates from an MC-PQ.

      Unit: 1 kilobit.
column17: Measurement starts when the HS-DSCH resources are set up. HS-FACH is not applicable\n      to this counter and HS-FACH transmissions do not consequently trigger the stepping of this counter.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Number of subframes in which no data with scheduling priority class 11 is transmitted
      although there is user data to be sent in the validated PQ. This user data is either waiting for
      first transmission, or data waiting for transmission (NACK is received or no ACK/NACK).
      If a subframe goes without scheduling priority class 11, that is, just carrying other scheduling
      priority classes or going totally empty, then the counter is stepped.
      If the buffer of an MC-PQ is emptied, due to prior scheduling in another cell in the same
      subframe, and no other buffer in the cell contains data the counter is not incremented.
      The counter reflects the cell perspective.
column17: The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup. HS-FACH does not\n      trigger the stepping of this counter. The counter is per cell and per subframe, meaning\n      increments with max 1 per subframe. A \subframe\" is a 2 ms TTI for HS-DSCH."

When HSDPA RBR QoS Profiling feature is ACTIVATED, then only the discards triggered by Iub congestions where the discards were done on the PQs that also experienced the frame loss are counted, that is, not the discards detected by RBR QoS profiling. When HSDPA RBR QoS Profiling feature is DEACTIVATED, then this counter counts all discards triggered by frame loss (Iub congestion). For discard due to Iub congestion this is done when the discard flag is checked. For MC PQs, the discards shall be counted in the HS-DSCH cell where the discard was performed.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16: Total amount of acknowledged MAC-hs/ehs data to UEs using any cell as serving HS-DSCH cell in 3MC mode.\nOnly acknowledged data originating from a PQ with scheduling priority class 06 is considered. The counter reflects the PQ perspective.\nUnit: 1 kilobit.
column17: Sampled each granularity period. HS-FACH is not applicable to this counter and HS-FACH transmissions do not trigger the stepping of this counter. The actual measurement starts when the HS-DSCH resources are set up.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16: Number of discards after RBR QoS profiling performed by the AQM feature for all Priority Queues (PQs) for Scheduling Priority Indicator (SPI) 05.
column17: The counter is only stepped if the HSDPA RBR QoS Profiling feature and the AQM feature are both activated and if SPI 05 is active for the AQM feature (set by IubDataStreams::hsAqmCongCtrlSpiOnOff). For discard due to Iub congestion this is done when the discard flag is checked. The discards are done for the PQs with the highest rates when normalized with the corresponding IubDataStreams::hsRbrWeight values. For MC PQs, the discards shall be counted in the HS-DSCH cell where the discard was performed.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
CQI reported by the UE. It is the true (unadjusted) CQI that is counted.
This counter is only relevant for UE units not using 64 QAM.

Bins:
[0]: Number of reported CQI with value 0
[1]: Number of reported CQI with value 1
...
[30]: Number of reported CQI with value 30
[31]: Number of reported CQI with invalid value
column17: The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup. HS-FACH is not applicable to this counter and HS-FACH transmissions do consequently not trigger the stepping of this counter. A UE unit in MC mode (with secondary serving HS-DSCH cell or cells activated) reports an independent CQI for each cell in the serving HS-DSCH cell set. The counter in each cell is therefore incremented accordingly. A UE unit in MC mode with deactivated secondary serving HS-DSCH cell or cells reports the CQI only for the serving HS-DSCH cell. Thus, only the counter in the serving HS-DSCH cell is incremented. The counter reflects the cell perspective.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Total amount of acknowledged data sent on MAC-hs level per scheduling priority class 09.
      The counter does not consider whether or not the transmitted data originates from an MC-PQ.
      The counter reflects the cell perspective.
      Unit: 1 kilobit.
column17: Measurement starts when the HS-DSCH resources are set up. HS-FACH is not applicable\n      to this counter and HS-FACH transmissions do not consequently trigger the stepping of this counter.

column10: Contains all PM counters for HsDschResources
column16:
Number of subframes in which no data with scheduling priority class 14 is transmitted
      although there is user data to be sent in the validated PQ. This user data is either waiting for
      first transmission, or data waiting for transmission (NACK is received or no ACK/NACK).
      If a subframe goes without scheduling priority class 14, that is, just carrying other scheduling
      priority classes or going totally empty, then the counter is stepped.
      If the buffer of an MC-PQ is emptied, due to prior scheduling in another cell in the same
      subframe, and no other buffer in the cell contains data the counter is not incremented.
      The counter reflects the cell perspective.
column17: The actual measurement is started when the HS-DSCH resources are setup. HS-FACH does not\n      trigger the stepping of this counter. The counter is per cell and per subframe, meaning\n      increments with max 1 per subframe. A \subframe\" is a 2 ms TTI for HS-DSCH."
