column16:
Number of new LSA that have been originated.

This number is incremented each time router originates new LSA.

Specification: RFC 4750.
column17: Link related to OSPF interface changes state, or during LSA refresh every 30 minutes.

column16: The total number of octets received on the interface, including framing characters.Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The number of inbound packets that contained errors preventing them from being deliverable to a higher-layer protocol. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
Total duration in milliseconds where LAG is operationally disabled due to Ethernet link failures for all encapsulated EthernetPorts , measured via loss of signal detection.
Distribution of the ingress throughput on the ethernet interface measured in octets per second.\nThe throughput samples are based on ifHCInOctets and are taken every second.
column17: Each bin is calculated as a percentile value at the end of the ROP period. 7 percentile values are presented in the bins [0,1,...,6] = [P0, P95, P96, P97, P98, P99, P100].

column16: Minimum duration in milliseconds where connection is lost due to that all links in Lag has Ethernet link failures, measured via loss of signal detection.

The number of multicast packets forwarded to a bridge or delivered to a higher (sub-)layer. Packets counted by ifInErrors, ifInUnknownProtos, ifInUnknownTags and ifInDiscards are not included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The number of packets received via the interface which were discarded because of an unknown or unsupported protocol. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The number of outbound packets which were discarded even though no errors had been detected, for example due to lack of buffer space or traffic shaping. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.

The number of inbound packets which were chosen to be discarded even though no errors had been detected to prevent their being deliverable to a higher-layer protocol. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The number of outbound packets that could not be transmitted because of errors. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The number of packets received via the interface which were discarded because of an unknown VLAN ID.
Distribution of the egress throughput on the ethernet interface measured in octets per second.\nThe throughput samples are based on ifHCOutOctets and are taken every second.
column17: Each bin is calculated as a percentile value at the end of the ROP period. 7 percentile values are presented in the bins [0,1,...,6] = [P0, P95, P96, P97, P98, P99, P100].

column16: The total number of multicast packets that are requested to be transmitted. Multicast packets counted by ifOutDiscards and ifOutErrors are included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
Maximum duration in milliseconds where connection is lost due to that all links in Lag has Ethernet link failures, measured via loss of signal detection.

The number of unicast packets  forwarded to a bridge or delivered to a higher (sub-)layer. Packets counted by ifInErrors, ifInUnknownProtos, ifInUnknownTags and ifInDiscards are not included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.

The number of broadcast packets forwarded to a bridge or delivered to a higher (sub-)layer. Packets counted by ifInErrors, ifInUnknownProtos, ifInUnknownTags and ifInDiscards are not included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The total number of broadcast packets that are requested to be transmitted. Broadcast packets counted by ifOutDiscards and ifOutErrors are included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
Total number of times connection is lost due to that all links in LAG has Ethernet link failures, measured via loss of signal detection.
The total number of unicast packets that are requested to be transmitted. Unicast packets counted by ifOutDiscards and ifOutErrors are included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The total number of octets transmitted out of the interface, including framing characters. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
Measured temperature for the SFP. Unit: 0.1 degree C
column17: Reports the last measured temperature on the SFP within the granularity period. A sample is taken every 900 seconds

column16: Measured TX bias current for the SFP. Unit: 0.01 mA
column17: Reports the last measured TX bias current on the SFP within the granularity period. A sample is taken every 900 seconds

column16: Measured TX output power for the SFP. Unit: 0.01 dBm. Value is reported with offset of +3000. To convert to dBm value use the formula dBm = ((value_reported - 3000)/100). For example, a reported value of 602 represents -23.98dBm.
column17: Reports the last measured TX output power on the SFP within the granularity period. A sample is taken every 900 seconds

column16: Measured RX output power for the SFP. Unit: 0.01 dBm. Value is reported with offset of +3000. To convert to dBm value use the formula dBm = ((value_reported - 3000)/100). For example, a reported value of 602 represents -23.98dBm.
column17: Reports the last measured RX output power on the SFP within the granularity period. A sample is taken every 900 seconds

column16: Measured voltage for the SFP. Unit: 0.0001 V (100 uV)
column17: Reports the last measured voltage on the SFP within the granularity period. A sample is taken every 900 seconds

column16:
Downlink carrier aggregation capability reported by UEs that use this cell as their PCell. Only the maximum number of SCells, where at least one of the carriers is TDD, is considered.

[0]: Number of UEs that are capable of FDD PCell plus one TDD SCell.
[1]: Number of UEs that are capable of FDD PCell plus two SCells, with at least one TDD SCell.
[2]: Number of UEs that are capable of FDD PCell plus three SCells, with at least one TDD SCell.
[3]: Number of UEs that are capable of FDD PCell plus four SCells, with at least one TDD SCell.

column16:
Total number of abnormal E-RAB releases by eNodeB for each cell for each QCI due to:
 - cell down time initiated automatically or
 - automated UE recovery.
Precondition: Initial Context Establishment procedure must first be successfully completed.
Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped for each E-RAB. Maps to a certain QCI that is released due to automatically initiated cell down time or due to automated UE recovery when data is in the UL or DL buffer. In the UL case, when a UE has multiple bearers coexisting and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the associated counter for the bearer is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column17: If there was data in the buffer at the time of release, then at reception of S1 message UE Context Release Command with internal cause codes considered abnormal (Radio Connection with UE is lost; Handover failure for the UE; UE pre-emption) when the RBS initiated the release. It can also be stepped at transmission of UE Context Release Request or Reset message by the RBS, or when a cell owned by that RBS is disabled (and that leads to internal RBS UE Context Release).\nNote. When the release cause indicates partial node restart, the actual status of the buffer is indeterminate at time of the restart therefore the bearer is instead considered active based on the latest RBS internal activity information (typically 1 second resolution), meaning that a bearer counted as \active\" could have been inactive for up to 1 second."

The release must also have been MME initiated. In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. column17: Stepped periodically at each sampling rate.

column16: The total number of unicast UL grants not designated for PUSCH data transmissions.  The grants are transmitted to UEs that have any bearer mapped to a QCI with serviceType of VoIP.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: It is pegged when a unicast UL grant is transmitted to a UE with any bearer mapped to a QCI with serviceType of VoIP, excluding the UL grants for message 3 for RRC connection setup. It is not pegged if corresponding UL data transmission is expected.\nThe counter is pegged when the EnhancedPdcchLa license is enabled regardless of the feature state.

column16: The number of successfully completed CFRA procedures. Measured when first UL-SCH message is received after detection of the CFRA preamble.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: This counter should be incremented when an UL-SCH message is successfully detected after a CFRA preamble has been received.

column16:
Number of Initial UE Context requests rejected by UE Context admission control due to Differentiated Admission Control licenses exceeded within this cell, recorded per UE ARP priority level.

PDF ranges:
[0]: N/A (invalid UE ARP priority level value)
[1]: Number of recorded events for UE ARP priority level 1
...
[15]: Number of recorded events for UE ARP priority level 15

Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The bin for the corresponding UE ARP priority level is stepped when Initial UE Context requests are rejected by UE Context admission control due to Differentiated Admission Control user licenses exceeded for the UE ARP.

column16: Number of RRC Connection Releases redirected to WCDMA, triggered by CSFB with NACC information.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: A CS Fallback with NACC information attempt is performed towards a WCDMA Frequency, defined as a RRC Connection Release with redirect information, due to a received CS Fallback Indicator set to CS Fallback Required in Initial Context Setup Request or UE Context Modification Request.

column16: The number of RRC Connection Release with redirect to WCDMA triggered either by CS Fallback Emergency or CS Fallback Emergency to WCDMA based on PSHO.\nScanner: Primary
column17: An Emergency CS Fallback attempt is performed towards a WCDMA Frequency, defined as an RRC Connection Release with redirect information, due to a received CS Fallback Indicator set to CS Fallback High Priority either in Initial Context Setup Request, or UE Context Modification Request. The counter steps either when release with redirect is preferred without measurement, or when handover is preferred but not possible, or when release with redirect based on measurement is preferred.

column16:
The number of lost packets in UL due to any of the following causes, differentiated per  QCI. Causes are either RLC re-assembly failure, HARQ failure or UE PDCP discarded  packets due to outdated PDUs.

Deprecated: Since L17A. Replaced by pmPdcpPktLostUlMissingPdus2Qci. Planned to be removed.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Per QCI, at detection of either RLC re-assembly failure, HARQ failure or UE PDCP discarded  packets due to outdated PDUs.

column16: Sum of all sample values recorded for number of UEs using TTI Bundling.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The counter accumulates values of the number of UEs using TTI Bundling from each sampling occasion.

column16: The total number of unicast UL grants transmitted.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: It is pegged when an unicast UL grant is transmitted excluding the UL grants for message 3.

column16:
The path loss distribution of the Radio Link Control (RLC) Service Data Units (SDU),  that are estimated in RLC to be lost for a VoIP bearer in uplink.

PDF ranges:
[0]: Number of samples less than or equals to 115 dB
[1]: Number of samples in range ]115..116] dB
[2]: Number of samples in range ]116..117] dB
...
[37]: Number of samples in range ]151..152] dB
[38]: Number of samples in range ]152..153] dB
[39]: Number of samples greater than 153 dB
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The counter is stepped when a RLC SDUs is estimated to be lost for a VoIP bearer of a UE that is configured for TTI Bundling.

column16: The accumulated interference power for PRB30\nUnit: mW * 2^(-44)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Samples summed over the measurement period. Measurements are averaged over receive antennas. One sample for each PRB per 40ms.

column16:
Cell distribution of sum of signaling intensity for handover and RRC Connection request in relation to control limit for cell connection intensity.

PDF Ranges:
[0]: [0..5] %
[1]: ]5..10] %
[2]: ]10..15] %
...
[19]: ]95..100] %
[20]: ]100..110] %
[21]: ]110..150] %
[22]: greater than150 %
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at reception of a message such as RRC Connection request, RRC connection reconfiguration, handover request or RRC connection release after time interval elapsed.

column16:
The total number of E-RAB Releases initiated by the MME considered as abnormal per cell per ARP Level. The counter is stepped if there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active).

PDF ranges:
[0]: Sum of E-RABs released with ARP priority value 0
[1]: Sum of E-RABs released with ARP priority value 1
....
[15]: Sum of E-RABs released with ARP priority value 15
Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The bin corresponding to the ARP level is stepped at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command with none of the causes Normal Release, Detach, CS Fallback Triggered or Redirection towards 1xRTT and there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active). The release must also have been MME initiated. In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter  is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column16: The number of failed handover preparations due to cell connection intensity control regulated by Dynamic Load Control.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at transmission of message Handover Preparatiuon Failure when triggered by intensity limitation in Dynamic Load Control.

column16: Number of attempts to start outgoing intra-LTE inter-frequency handover preparation, triggered by bad UL quality in the source cell.\nUsed when feature Uplink-Triggered Inter-Frequency Mobility is activated.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when source cell starts a handover preparation procedure due to bad UL quality in source cell.

column16:
Number of configured DL LAA SCell CCs, for UEs that use this cell as their PCell CC.

PDF ranges:
[0]: Number of DL LAA CA-capable UEs that are not configured with any LAA SCell
[1]: Number of DL LAA CA-capable UEs that are configured with one LAA SCell
[2]: Number of DL LAA CA-capable UEs that are configured with two LAA SCells
[3]: Number of DL LAA CA-capable UEs that are configured with three LAA SCells
[4]: Number of DL LAA CA-capable UEs that are configured with four LAA SCells
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: When DL LAA SCell is configured or de-configured for UE, two things happen. Counter that corresponds to number of configured LAA SCells before the configuration or de-configuration is decremented.\nCounter that corresponds to number of configured LAA SCells after configuration or de-configuration is incremented.

column16: The accumulated sum of all sub-band 2 CQI reported by UEs in the cell for rank 2 transmissions. The average value of the reported sub-band 2 CQI within the measurement period can be obtained in conjunction with counter pmRadioUeRepCqi2SubbandSamp.\nThe counter is defined according to 32.425.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17:
Samples summed over the measurement period. One sample per UE aperiodic rank 2 CQI report.
This counter is for rank 2 (two codewords) CQI reports.
The counter is defined according to 32.425 Section 4.10.1.2
Valid UE reported CQI values range from 0 to 15
Note for CQI/PMI/RI reporting mode 3-1 or 2-1, there will be a different Sub-band CQI value for each codeword. In this case both CQI values shall be added to the counter and are counted as two samples.

column16:
The number of RRC Connection Reestablishment attempts from bandwidth reduced UEs.

PDF ranges:
[0]: CE level 0
[1]: CE level 1
[2]: CE level 2
[3]: CE level 3
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: A RRC Connection Reestablishment Request message is received from bandwidth reduced UEs.

column16:
Total number of abnormal E-RAB releases by eNodeB for each cell for each QCI due to:
 - cell down time initiated automatically caused by a partial node restart or
 - automated UE recovery.
Precondition: Initial Context Establishment procedure must first be successfully completed and that there is data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active).
Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped for each E-RAB. Maps to a certain QCI that is released due to automatically initiated cell down time caused by a partial node restart or due to automated UE recovery when data is in the UL or DL buffer. In the UL case, when a UE has multiple bearers coexisting and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the associated counter for the bearer is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column16: Number of Session Continuity RRC Connection Release with redirect to GERAN based on B2 measurement report with trigger quantity RSRP.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: A RRC Connection Release with redirect information to GERAN when triggered by B2 measurement report with RSRP.

column16: The number of successful outgoing intra LTE intra frequency handovers made by Tune-out UEs.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17:
UE CONTEXT RELEASE COMMAND received in the source eNodeB from the MME with the cause Handover Triggered (S1 handover)
or
UE CONTEXT RELEASE received in the source eNodeB from the target eNodeB (X2 handover)
or
Internal eNodeB trigger (corresponding to UE CONTEXT RELEASE) received when the UE has changed cell during an intra eNodeB handover.

Stepped in case UE type is Tune-out

column16: Maximum utilization of SR resources in the medium resource pool.\nUnit: %\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: When pool resource utilization increased after a successful SR resource allocation in the pool.

column16: The total number of unsuccessful HARQ transmissions in the downlink direction using a 16QAM modulation.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: To decide if it was failed is based on the HARQ NACK from the UE.

column16: The number of VoLTE sessions (radio bearers with serviceType= VOIP) of satisfactory quality.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The counter is incremented when the VoIP session, i.e. the time when a radio bearer which carries VoIP traffic is established, has had a satisfactory VoIP quality. This means that at least the minimum required amount of VoIP packets are available for the measurement, and that at least 99% of the VoIP packets for the VoIP session had an air interface delay within the packet delay budget. If the above conditions are met then counters can be incremented at the end of the ROP (Recording output period) or when the voice bearer is released by ERAB Release procedure or both of them

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

The DL MAC latency time for data bursts that arrive when the UE is in DRX Inactive state and in UL In-sync state. It is accumulated over all active DRBs with the corresponding QCI value.

When carrier aggregation is used, DL MAC DRB latency for all component carriers is registered on the primary cell for the UE.
Compressed: True
Unit: ms
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Counts time from when data arrives to the empty PDCP SDU buffer while MAC DRB buffer is also empty, until the first data on the MAC layer is transmitted. Includes only bursts that start when the UE is in DRX Inactive state and UL In-sync state.\n\nEach bin accumulates latency for all DRBs with the corresponding QCI value. Continuous measurement for each DRB aggregated to cell level.

column16: This measurement provides the number of S1 Signaling connection establishment attempts with RRC Connection Request Establishment cause Mobile Originating Data.\nScanner: Primary
column17: Stepped at transmission of Initial UE message with RRC Connection Request Establishment cause Mobile Originating Data.

column16: Total number of DRB packets (PDCP SDUs) forwarded to target cell at handover for downlink sessions.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Packet forwarding is started when source cell transmit RRCConnectionReconfiguration and is stopped when source receives the end marker or  when the source receives UE Context Release from target or timer tHODataFwdReordering has expiered.

column16:
The total number of abnormal E-RAB Releases for each cell for each QCI initiated by the RBS due to license reject.
Compressed: true.

Deprecated: Since L16A. Planned to be removed.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command. Preconditions are that procedure Initial Context Establishment is first successfully completed. Also, when internal cause codes are considered abnormal, and when the RBS initiated the release.

column16: The total number of abnormal E-RAB releases for each cell due to S1 Interface Down, X2 Interface Down, or Transport Resource Unavailable. Preconditions are that procedure Initial Context Establishment is first successfully completed and there is data in the UL or DL buffer.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: If there is data in the buffer at the time of release of an E-RAB and because the S1 interface or X2 interface is lost, or S1 bearer error indication is received. In the UL case, when a UE has multiple bearers coexisting and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the associated counter for the bearer is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column16: The sum of the contributions from each UE in the cell of the number of active DRBs in the downlink direction.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Each TTI, the counter shall be increased with the number of DRBs that are considered active (i.e. that have data in the downlink buffer).

column16: The number of Incoming Handover Preparation Failure messages sent by the target eNB due to lack of license for handover.\nScanner: Primary
column17: Handover preparation fail due to the serviceState value is INOPERABLE for the optional feature, \Intra LTE inter frequency handover\" in the target eNB."

column16: Number of Session Continuity RRC Connection Release with redirect to CDMA2000 based on A2 measurement report with trigger quantity RSRP.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: A RRC Connection Release with redirect information to CDMA2000 when triggered by A2_Search, A2_Outer_Search or A2_Critical measurement report with RSRP.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
Number of TTIs for which CRS:es in the PDCCH region are fully or partially blanked.\nUnit: subframes\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: When ELC decides to mute parts of the CRS:es that are contained in the PDCCH region, this counter is stepped once.

column16: The total number of Physical Resource Block (PRB) pairs used for paging.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: This measurement is applicable to the Paging Control Channel (PCCH) on the Physical Downlink Shared Channel (PDSCH).

column16: The sum of the contributions from each UE in the cell of the number of active DRBs in the uplink direction.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Each TTI, the counter shall be increased with the number of DRBs that are considered active (i.e. that are considered to have data in the uplink buffer).

column16: The accumulated interference power for PRB37\nUnit: mW * 2^(-44)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Samples summed over the measurement period. Measurements are averaged over receive antennas. One sample for each PRB per 40ms.

column16: The accumulated interference power for PRB40\nUnit: mW * 2^(-44)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Samples summed over the measurement period. Measurements are averaged over receive antennas. One sample for each PRB per 40ms.

column16: New unicast DL assignments that are transmitted during DRX onDuration to UEs with bearer mapped to QCI with VoIP service type. Reception must be confirmed by corresponding ACK or NACK for any transport block. DL assignments are excluded if this cell is SCell for those UEs.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17:
Stepped when detecting a HARQ ACK or NACK for any transport block.
The ACK/NACK must be confirmed and correspond to a new unicast DL assignment.
DL assignment must be for any bearer mapped to a QCI with serviceType set to VoIP.
DL assignment must be transmitted during DRX onDuration.
This cell is not a secondary cell of the UE.

column16: The total number of abnormal E-RAB Releases triggered by eNB per cell.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command where the cause value indicates system (abnormal) release with the pre-condition that the Initial Context Establishment procedure must first have been successfully completed. The release must also have been eNB initiated.

column16: The total number of successful S1 signaling connection establishments with Establishment cause High Priority Access.\nScanner: Primary
column17: Stepped at first message received on this UE-associated logical S1-connection, if the RRC Connection Request Establishment cause was Establishment cause High Priority Access.

column16: The number of successful intra LTE intra frequency handover preparations.\nScanner: Primary
column17:
HANDOVER COMMAND message is received by the source eNodeB from the MME (S1 handover)
or
HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE message is received by the source eNodeB from the target eNodeB (X2 handover)
or
Internal eNodeB trigger (corresponding to HANDOVER REQUEST ACKNOWLEDGE) received when target cell informs source cell that UE resources has been reserved (intra eNodeB handover)

column16:

[4]: 40% less than utilization less than or equals to 50%
[5]: 50% less than utilization less than or equals to 60%
[6]: 60% less than utilization less than or equals to 70%
[7]: 70% less than utilization less than or equals to 80%
[8]: 80% less than utilization less than or equals to 90%
[9]: 90% less than utilization less than or equals to 100%
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: An appropriate bin is incremented in every radio subframe.

column16: The accumulated interference power for PRB83\nUnit: mW * 2^(-44)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Samples summed over the measurement period. Measurements are averaged over receive antennas. One sample for each PRB per 40ms.

column16: The total number of successful S1 signaling connection establishments with Establishment cause Mobile Originating Signaling.\nScanner: Primary
column17: Stepped at first message received on this UE-associated logical S1-connection, if the RRC Connection Request Establishment cause was Establishment cause Mobile Originating Signaling.

column16:
Successful initial E-RAB Establishments per ARP value.

[1]: Sum of successful initial E-RAB Establishment with ARP priority value 1

column16:
Number of data bursts used for DL MAC latency measurements that arrive when the UE is in DRX inactivity period and in UL In-sync state.

Deprecated: Since L16A. Replaced by counter pmMacTimeDlDrxSyncSampQci. Planned to be removed.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped each time a new value is added to the counter pmMacLatTimeQciDlDrxSyncSum.\n\nContinuous measurement for each DRB with the QCI in the range, on each UE, aggregated to cell level.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
Number of RRC Connection Releases redirected to GSM, triggered by CSFB with NACC information.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

Release and redirect is based on NACC information.

column16: The accumulated sum of all sub-band 11 CQI reported by UEs in the cell for rank 2 transmissions. column17:
Samples summed over the measurement period. One sample per UE aperiodic rank 2 CQI report.
This counter is for rank 2 (two codewords) CQI reports.

Valid UE reported CQI values range from 0 to 15
Note for CQI/PMI/RI reporting mode 3-1 or 2-1, there will be a different Sub-band CQI value for each codeword. In this case both CQI values shall be added to the counter and are counted as two samples.

column16: The accumulated interference power for PRB97\nUnit: mW * 2^(-44)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Samples summed over the measurement period. Measurements are averaged over receive antennas. One sample for each PRB per 40ms.

column16: The total number of successfully added E-RABs with Privileged Access. Added E-RABs are all E-RABs present in S1 message E-RAB Setup Request.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at sending of E-RAB Setup Response for each successfully setup E-RAB that has the given ARP Priority Level equal to or below AdmissionControl::paArpOverride.

column16: The accumulated interference power for PRB96\nUnit: mW * 2^(-44)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Samples summed over the measurement period. Measurements are averaged over receive antennas. One sample for each PRB per 40ms.

The reported CQI values related to rank 4 transmissions from UEs in higher order modulation (HOM) mode (which supports 256 QAM) in a distribution.

[0]: CQI = 0
[1]: CQI = 1
[2]: CQI = 2
[3]: CQI = 3
[4]: CQI = 4
[5]: CQI = 5
[6]: CQI = 6

column16: Number of UE Context Fetch procedures successfully completed during X2 handover preparation.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: X2 UE Context Release message is received from target eNodeB after successful UE Context Fetch procedure. UE Context Fetch procedure was triggered during X2 handover preparation.

column16: Peak number of UEs considered active in the uplink direction, i.e. the UE is considered to have data in its buffer. The value is a maximum of a set of samples, where each sample is an average of active UEs per ms (throughout the frame), during a sample period shorter than the ROP. Bandwidth-reduced UEs are excluded from this measurement.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The counter is set to peak sample recognized at the end of each Recording Output Period (ROP).

column16: Total number of prescheduled UEs in the uplink, including both initial transmissions and HARQ re-transmissions, where the transport block contained data mapped to a LCG in UL.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when the transport block scheduled by prescheduling contains data mapped to a LCG in UL.

column16: The total number of abnormal ERAB releases per cell by the eNB due to handover execution failure and that there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active).\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: If there was data in the buffer at the time of release, and the release is due to that executed handover fails and the UE is considered dropped. In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter  is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column16: See Condition.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at reception of S1 message UE Context Release Command with internal cause codes considered abnormal (Radio Connection with UE is lost; Handover failure for the UE; UE pre-emption) when the RBS initiated the release. It can also be stepped at transmission of UE Context Release Request or Reset message by the RBS, or when a cell owned by that RBS is disabled (and that leads to internal RBS UE Context Release).

column16: The accumulated interference power for PRB10\nUnit: mW * 2^(-44)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Samples summed over the measurement period. Measurements are averaged over receive antennas. One sample for each PRB per 40ms.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
Total number of abnormal E-RAB Releases for each cell initiated by the eNodeB. The UE is in Out-of-Sync mode and has data in the buffers.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17:
Stepped if the UE is in Out-of-Sync state, has data in any of its buffers and at:
- Reception of E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command with the internal cause code is considered as abnormal
- Transmission of E-RAB Release Indication or UE Context Release Request
- Transmission of Reset message by the RBS
- Internal RBS UE Context Release due to disabling of a cell owned by that RBS

column16: Total of assumed successfully transferred data volume on MAC level in the DL for external SCell (ESCell) traffic as measured and reported on the ESCell.\nUnit: kilobit (1 000 bits)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when a DL TB is received from a master eNodeB and indicates first HARQ transmission.

column16: The number of successful RRC Connection Reestablishments.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: A RRC Connection Reestablishment Complete messages is received.

column16: The total number of occasions when an uplink grant was meant for HARQ transmission of a transport block using QPSK modulation in the uplink direction, where DTX is considered the reason for no reception of HARQ in uplink in the eNB.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: To decide if it was DTX is based on not receiving a granted uplink transmission using QPSK modulation.

column16:
Total number of abnormal E-RAB releases initiated by the eNodeB due to handover failure. The UE is in Out-Of-Sync mode and has data in the buffers.

Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped if the UE is in Out-of-Sync state, has data in any of its buffers and the E-RAB release is due to handover failure.

column16: This measurement provides the number of S1 Signaling connection establishment attempts for any establishment cause.\nScanner: Primary

Distribution of the DeltaSINR for PUSCH with eRAN with UL CoMP enabled.

[1]: -2less thanDeltaSINR less than or equals to 0
[2]: 0 less than DeltaSINR less than or equals to 2
[3]: 2 less than DeltaSINR less than or equals to 4

column16:
Abnormal E-RAB Releases initiated by RBS (per cell per ARP).Stepped if data was present in UL or DL buffers.

[0]: Sum of active E-RABs released with ARP priority value 0
[1]: Sum of active E-RABs released with ARP priority value 1
....
[15]: Sum of active E-RABs released with ARP priority value 15

column17: If there was data in the buffer at the time of release, then stepped at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command, for E-RAB/s with the specific ARP Priority Level, when internal cause codes considered abnormal (Radio Connection with UE is lost; Handover failure for the UE; Non admitted E-RABs by target cell at successful handover for the UE; UE pre-emption; Bearer pre-emption) when the RBS initiated the release. It can also be stepped at transmission of Reset message by the RBS, or when a cell owned by that RBS is disabled (and that leads to internal RBS UE Context Release). In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.\nNote. When the release cause indicates partial node restart, the actual status of the buffer is indeterminate at time of the restart therefore the bearer is instead considered active based on the latest RBS internal activity information (typically 1 second resolution), meaning that a bearer counted as \active\" could have been inactive for up to 1 second."

column16:

column16: The accumulated sum of all sub-band 7 CQI reported by UEs in the cell for rank 1 transmissions. column16:

column17: Samples summed over the measurement period. Measurements are averaged over receive antennas. One sample for each PRB per 40ms.

This is suitable for PDCP timebase.

column16: The UL volume transfer time used for UL UE Throughput. It comprises of time periods from when the 5th MAC SDU data reception of an UL buffer transfer on Uu until the buffer is emptied, excluding the TTI emptying the buffer.\nUnit: ms\nScanner: Primary
column17: Continuous measurement for UEs aggregated to cell level.

column16: Number of UEs reporting IRAT-ParametersGUTRA while attaching to the LTE cell.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

Total number of abnormal E-RAB releases by eNodeB for each cell for each QCI due to:
 - cell down time initiated automatically or by manual intervention or
 - automated UE recovery.
Precondition: Initial Context Establishment procedure must first be successfully completed and that there is data in either the UL or DL buffer.
Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped for each E-RAB. Maps to a certain QCI that is released due to cell down time (initiated automatically or by manual intervention) or due to automated UE recovery when data is in the UL or DL buffer. In the UL case, when a UE has multiple bearers coexisting and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the associated counter for the bearer is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column16:
DL MAC SDU volume transmitted on all DRBs for each UE.
When carrier aggregation is used, a PDCP SDU can be transmitted over multiple cells, PCell or SCells. DL MAC transmitted volume over all carriers is registered on PCell.

Deprecated: Since 18.Q3. Planned to be removed.

column16:
Delay distribution between reception of random access message 3 and successful transmission of random access message 4. Only counts message 4s that contain a contention resolution identity and no RRC message or a contention resolution identity and an RRC connection reject or an RRC connection re-establishment reject message.

PDF ranges:
[0]: less than or equals to 8 ms
[1]: ]8..16] ms
[2]: ]16..24] ms
[3]: ]24..32] ms
[4]: ]32..40] ms
[5]: ]40..48] ms
[6]: ]48..56] ms
[7]: ]56..64] ms
[8]: greater than 64 ms
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The counter is stepped when the eNB has received a positive acknowledgement of a random access message 4 from the UE. The delay is measured from the reception of the message 3 to the transmission of the message 4. Only a message 4 that contains a contention resolution identifier and no RRC message or that contains a contention resolution identifier and an RRC connection reject or an RRC connection re-establishment reject is counted.

column16: Total number of CCEs used for Prescheduling UL grants, including both initial transmissions and adaptive retransmissions.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: The total number of added E-RAB Establishment attempts with Privileged Access. Added E-RABs are all E-RABs present in S1 message E-RAB Setup Request.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at reception of E-RAB Setup Request for each E-RAB that has the given ARP Priority Level equal to or below AdmissionControl::paArpOverride.

column16: The total number of Physical Resource Block (PRB) pairs used for Signaling Radio Bearers (SRB) in the uplink.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: This measurement is applicable to Dedicated Control Channels (DCCH) and Common Control Channels (CCCH) on the Physical Uplink Shared Channel (PUSCH).

column16: The accumulated interference power for PRB25\nUnit: mW * 2^(-44)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

The release must also have been eNB initiated.

column17: Stepped for each UE that is released due to cell down time (initiated automatically) caused by a partial node restart or due to automated UE recovery.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

...

column16: Total B2 measurement reports received.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when traffic measurement report received from UE indicates a better inter-RAT cell based on Event B2, either RSRP or RSRQ triggered, 'PCell becomes worse than threshold1 and inter RAT neighbour becomes better than threshold2'.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
The total number of E-RAB Releases initiated by the MME considered as abnormal. The counter is stepped if there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active).\nScanner: Primary
column17: Stepped at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release with none of the causes Normal Release, Handover Successful, User Inactivity, Detach, CS Fallback Triggered, Inter-RAT Redirection, UE Not available for PS Service or Redirection towards 1xRTT and there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active). The release must also have been MME initiated. In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter  is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column16: Number of Session Continuity RRC Connection Release with redirect to GERAN based on A2 measurement report with trigger quantity RSRQ.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: A RRC Connection Release with redirect information to GERAN when triggered by A2_Search, A2_Outer_Search or A2_Critical measurement report with RSRQ.

column16:

Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Pegs once per sample period, indicating how many 5-second samples were aggregated in the ROP. This can vary from 180 by +/- 1.
The counter is stepped periodically at each measurement interval of CCE utilization level for each cell.

column16:
Number of attempted handover executions that are:
- outgoing intra-LTE,
- inter-frequency and
- to Hybrid CSG cell.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17:
Stepped if all are true:
- Source eNodeB initiated the inter-frequency Hybrid CSG cell handover
- RRC CONNECTION RECONFIGURATION message including the mobilityControlInformation is sent to the UE from the source eNodeB and
- If caused by feature Mobility to CSG Cells.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
The number of UE that are not satisfied with their VoIP quality.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The counter is incremented when it has been determined that a UE is not satisfied with its VoIP quality. This can be caused due to two conditions: (1) At least the minimume amount of VoIP packets is available for the measurement and less than 99% of the VoIP packets of the UE had an air interface delay within the packet delay budget.  (2)  50% or less of the VoIP packets of the UE had an air interface delay within the packet delay budget, regardless of the amount of VoIP packets for measurement.

column16:
The total volume (PDCP SDU) on Data Radio Bearers that has been transferred (acknowledged by the UE) in the downlink direction in the last TTI when a buffer is emptied.

When carrier aggregation is used, a PDCP SDU can be sent over multiple cells (PCell/SCell(s)). The total volume (PDCP SDU) on Data Radio Bearers that has been transferred (acknowledged by the UE) in the downlink direction in the last TTI when a buffer is emptied is measured on PCell.
Unit: kilobit (1 000 bits)
Scanner: Primary
column17: Stepped before ROHC for UEs aggregated to cell level.

column16:
Aggregated DL Latency for a measurement period. The effective DL Latency time comprises the time from PDCP DRB SDU entering the buffer until the first data has been transmitted to the UE.

When carrier aggregation is used, the DL Latency for all component carriers is registered on the UE's primary component carrier (PCell).
Unit: ms
Scanner: Primary
column17: Measurement for UEs aggregated to cell level. Only PDCP SDUs that enters an empty buffer are measured. Samples during handover are excluded since they can distort the interpretation of the result (due to packet forwarding, the target cell might have to buffer data before it is possible to schedule the UE in the target cell, hence it would be an increased Latency measurement if it would be included. It would however not lead to a degraded performance for the end-user, due to packet forwarding).

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

Total A2 measurement reports received because critical threshold is reached with trigger quantity RSRP.\nUsed when feature Mobility Control at Poor Coverage is active.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when traffic measurement report received from UE indicates bad coverage. Event A2_Critical RSRP triggered.

column16:

[1]: Number of UEs that are DL CA-capable of PCell plus one SCell.
[2]: Number of UEs that are DL CA-capable of PCell plus two SCells.
[3]: Number of UEs that are DL CA-capable of PCell plus three SCells.
[4]: Number of UEs that are DL CA-capable of PCell plus four SCells.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: When UE capability is registered, the internal counter that corresponds to the maximum number of downlink SCells of any duplex mode is incremented. When UE capability is deregistered, the counter that corresponds is decremented. The values are sampled periodically and added to the statistics counter in each bin.

column16: Number of UE Context Fetch procedures successfully completed during SRVCC handover to UTRAN execution.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column17: If there was data in the buffer at the time of release of a GBR E-RAB, then the bin for the corresponding ARP priority level is stepped at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command when internal cause codes considered abnormal (Radio Connection with UE is lost; Handover failure for the UE; Non admitted E-RABs by target cell at successful handover for the UE; UE pre-emption; Bearer pre-emption) when the RBS initiated the release. It can also be stepped at transmission of Reset message by the RBS, or when a cell owned by that RBS is disabled (and that leads to internal RBS UE Context Release). In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.\nNote: When the release cause indicates partial node restart, the actual status of the buffer is indeterminate at time of the restart therefore the bearer is instead considered active based on the latest RBS internal activity information (typically 1 second resolution), meaning that a bearer counted as \active\" could have been inactive for up to 1 second."

When carrier aggregation is used, a PDCP SDU can be sent over multiple cells (PCell/SCell(s)). The total volume (PDCP SDU) on Data Radio Bearers that has been transmitted in the downlink direction in the PDCP layer for the UEs served by PLMN0 is measured on PCell.

Samples summed over the measurement period. One sample per UE aperiodic rank 2 CQI report.

column16:
Total number of abnormal E-RAB releases by eNodeB for each cell for each QCI due to:
 - cell down time initiated automatically caused by a partial node restart or
 - automated UE recovery.
Precondition: Initial Context Establishment procedure must first be successfully completed.
Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped for each E-RAB. Maps to a certain QCI that is released due to automatically initiated cell down time caused by a partial node restart or due to automated UE recovery when data is in the UL or DL buffer. In the UL case, when a UE has multiple bearers coexisting and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the associated counter for the bearer is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column16: The total number of E-RAB releases by the MME per QCI with a cause regarded as abnormal.\nCompressed: True.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The bin corresponding to the QCI of the E-RAB is stepped at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release with none of the causes Normal Release, Handover Successful, User Inactivity, Detach, CS Fallback Triggered, Inter-RAT Redirection, UE Not available for PS Service or Redirection towards 1xRTT. The release must also have been MME initiated.

column16: The number of UE that are satisfied with their VoIP quality.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The counter is incremented when it has been determined that a UE is satisfied with its VoIP quality. This means that at least the minimume amount of VoIP packets is available for the measurement and that at least 99% of the VoIP packets of the UE had an air interface delay within the packet delay budget.

column16: The total number of RRC Connection Request attempts that are considered as re-attempts for Establishment cause Mobile Terminating Access.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at reception of RRC message RRC Connection Request with Establishment cause Mobile Terminating Access AND while an RRC Connection Setup is already ongoing for that S-TMSI.

column16: The total number of abnormal E-RAB releases by eNodeB for each cell for each QCI because contact with the UE is lost. Preconditions are that  procedure Initial Context Establishment is first successfully completed and that there is data in the UL or DL buffer.\nCompressed: true.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped for each E-RAB. Maps to a certain QCI that the radio connection towards the UE is unreachable by the RBS when data is in the UL or DL buffer. In the UL case, when a UE has multiple bearers coexisting and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the associated counter for the bearer is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column17: The counter is incremented when the VoIP session, i.e. the time when a radio bearer which carries VoIP traffic is established, has had an unsatisfactory VoIP quality. This can be caused by two conditions: (1) At least the minimum required amount of VoIP packets are available for the measurement and less than 99% of the VoIP packets for the VoIP session had an air interface delay within the packet delay budget. (2) 50% or less of the VoIP packets of the VoIP session had an air interface delay within the packet delay budget, regardless of the amount of VoIP packets for measurement. If the above conditions are met then counters can be incremented at the end of the ROP (Recording Output Period) or when the voice bearer is released by ERAB Release procedure or both of them.

column16:

column17: When the cell fails to broadcast an RRC Paging within a certain time (pagingDiscardTimer), e.g. due to congestion, the Paging is discarded and this counter is incremented by the number of included Paging Records in the discarded Paging message.

column16: Total A2 event reports because the critical threshold is reached with trigger quantity UL SINR. Counter is used when the feature Uplink-Triggered Inter-Frequency Mobility is activated.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16:

The release must also have been MME initiated.

column16:
The DL transmission time used for DL DRB Throughput per QCI. It comprises of time periods from when the first piece of data in a data burst is transmitted until the second last piece of data in the data burst is transmitted.

When carrier aggregation is used, the DL transmission time used for DL DRB Throughput per QCI is registered on the UE's primary component carrier (PCell).

Scanner: Primary

column16: The total number of abnormal E-RAB releases by eNodeB for each cell for each QCI due to handover preparation and there is data in the UL or DL buffer.\nCompressed: true.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the  associated counter for the bearer is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column17: Pegs once per sample period, indicating how many 5-second samples were aggregated in the ROP. This can vary from 180 by +/- 1.

column16: The counter counts the number of times a HARQ-process for random access message 4 fails for cases where the contention resolution counter has not expired. The counter only counts message 4s that contain a contention resolution identity and no RRC message or a contention resolution identity and an RRC connection reject or an RRC connection re-establishment reject message.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The counter is stepped when the time of the transmit of the last HARQ transmission is within the contention resolution timer. Only a message 4 that contains a contention resolution identifier and no RRC message or that contains a contention resolution identifier and an RRC connection reject or an RRC connection re-establishment reject is counted.

column16:
The DL MAC latency time for data bursts that arrive when the UE is in DRX Active state and in UL Out-of-sync state. It is accumulated over all active DRBs with the corresponding QCI value.


When carrier aggregation is used, DL MAC DRB latency for all component carriers is registered on the primary cell for the UE.
Compressed: True
Unit: ms
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Counts time from when data arrives to the empty PDCP SDU buffer while MAC DRB buffer is also empty, until the first data on the MAC layer is transmitted. Includes only bursts that start when the UE is in DRX Active state and UL Out-of-sync state.\n\nEach bin accumulates latency for all DRBs with the corresponding QCI value. Continuous measurement for each DRB aggregated to cell level.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nCompressed: True\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

Number of S1 signaling connection establishment attempts with RRC connection request establishment cause delay tolerant access from bandwidth reduced UEs, per PRACH Coverage Enhancement (CE) level.

PDF ranges:
[0]: CE level 0
[1]: CE level 1
[2]: CE level 2
[3]: CE level 3
Scanner: Primary
column17: Stepped at transmission of Initial UE message with RRC Connection Request Establishment cause Delay Tolerant Access.

column16: The total number of abnormal E-RAB releases for each cell for each QCI due to S1 Interface Down, X2 Interface Down or Transport Resource Unavailable. Preconditions are that procedure Initial Context Establishment  is first successfully completed and there is data in the UL or DL buffer.\nCompressed: true.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped for each E-RAB. Maps to a certain QCI that is released because S1 interface or X2 interface is lost. S1 bearer error indication is received when data is in the UL or DL buffer. In the UL case, when a UE has multiple bearers coexisting and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the associated counter for the bearer is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column16:
Number of added E-RAB establishment requests rejected by Differentiated Admission Control due to MSR capacity within this cell, recorded per ARP priority level.

PDF ranges:
[0]: N/A (invalid ARP priority level value)
[1]: Number of recorded events for ARP priority level 1
...
[15]: Number of recorded events for ARP priority level 15

Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The bin for the corresponding ARP priority level is stepped when added E-RAB establishment requests are rejected by Differentiated Admission Control due to capacity exceeded on any MSR. Added E-RABs are all E-RABs present in S1 message E-RAB Setup Request.

column16: The total number of abnormal UE Contexts Releases initiated by the RBS due to license reject.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at reception of S1 message UE Context Release Command when internal cause codes are considered abnormal. Occurs when encryption or integrity algorithms are not supported by the eNB. The cause is either: license Limited Service Mode Emergency Call Support is not operable, or no common algorithms found when the RBS initiated the release.

column16: Number of RRC Connection Re-establishment attempts differentiated for each QCI. Counter is only stepped if Context Fetch procedure is successful.\nCompressed: True\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: During a re-establishment attempt, the counter is stepped only after a successful Context Fetch procedure for each E-RAB that has the given QCI value.

column16: The total number of occasions when a downlink HARQ feedback for a transport block using 16QAM modulation was not received from an UE and DTX is considered the reason.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: To decide if it was DTX is based on not receiving any HARQ feedback on a transport block sent using 16QAM modulation.

column16: The total number of unsuccessful RLC PDU and RLC PDU segment transmissions (NACKs) in the uplink direction.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Continuous measurement for Radio Bearers aggregated to cell level.

column16: Number of received A5 inter-frequency measurement reports for target cell measurements triggered by bad UL quality in the source cell.\nUsed when feature Uplink-Triggered Inter-Frequency Mobility is activated.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when A5 inter-frequency measurement report received from UE for target cell measurements triggered by bad UL quality.

column16: New unicast DL assignments transmitted during DRX onDuration.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when a new unicast DL assignment to a specific UE is transmitted during DRX onDuration excluding DL assignments for message 2.

column16: The total number of initial E-RAB Establishment attempts with Privileged Access. Initial E-RABs are all E-RABs present in the S1 message Initial Context Setup Request.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at reception of Initial Context Setup Request for each E-RAB that has the given ARP Priority Level equal to or below AdmissionControl::paArpOverride.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

Peak number of UEs that connected on bandwidth reduced PRACH using Coverage Enhancement level 3 and that are considered active in the UL direction. A UE is considered active if it has data in its buffer. The value is a maximum of a set of samples, where each sample is an average of active UEs per ms (throughout the frame), during a sample period shorter than the ROP.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Set to peak sample recognized during the Recording Output Period (ROP).

column16: The total number of RRC Connection Request attempts with establishment cause highPriorityAccess\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at reception of RRC message RRC Connection Request with establishment cause highPriorityAccess

column16:
The total number of initial E-RAB Establishment attempts per ARP value. Initial E-RABs are all E-RABs present in the S1 message Initial Context Setup Request.

[1]: Sum of initial E-RAB Establish Attempts with ARP priority value 1
...
[15]: Sum of initial E-RAB Establish Attempts with ARP priority value 15

column17: Stepped at reception of Initial Context Setup Request for each E-RAB that has the given ARP Priority Level.

column16: Number of transport blocks on MAC level scheduled in UL where UE is not considered to be power-limited. Transport blocks are excluded if scheduled for UEs with activated secondary carrier that is configured for UL transmissions.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: A Transport Block is considered to be power limited when the estimated required transmit power is higher than the UE maximum transmit power.

column16:
Total number of abnormal UE context releases by eNodeB due to:
 - cell down time (initiated automatically) caused by a partial node restart or
 - automated UE recovery.
Precondition: There is data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active).
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Counts the total number of abnormal UE context releases by the eNodeB due to cell down time (initiated automatically) caused by a partial node restart or due to automated UE recovery when data was in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active).

column16: The number of rejected RRC Connection setup triggered by the MP Overload state.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped at transmission of RRC message RRC Connection Reject when MP load control function in the RBS indicates overload state.

column16:
Number of attempted handover executions that are:
- outgoing intra-LTE,
- inter-frequency and
- to closed access mode CSG cell.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17:
Stepped if all are true:
- Source eNodeB initiated the inter-frequency CSG cell handover
- RRC CONNECTION RECONFIGURATION message including the mobilityControlInformation is sent to the UE from the source eNodeB and
- If caused by feature Mobility to CSG Cells.

column16: The number of Radio Link Control (RLC) Service Data Units (SDU), that is PDCP SDUs, in UL that are received within the PDB in uplink. Only applicable for VoIP. Note: If ROHC is enabled, pmPdcpPktPdbUlOkVoip might be greater than pmPdcpPktReceivedUlQci due to difference in ROHC control packets handling between the counters.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Incremented when a VoIP packet has an air interface delay within the packet delay budget.

column16: The accumulated sum of all sub-band 0 CQI reported by UEs in the cell for rank 2 transmissions. The average value of the reported sub-band 0 CQI within the measurement period can be obtained in conjunction with counter pmRadioUeRepCqi2SubbandSamp.\nThe counter is defined according to 32.425.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17:
Samples summed over the measurement period. One sample per UE aperiodic rank 2 CQI report.
This counter is for rank 2 (two codewords) CQI reports.
The counter is defined according to 32.425 Section 4.10.1.2
Valid UE reported CQI values range from 0 to 15
Note for CQI/PMI/RI reporting mode 3-1 or 2-1, there will be a different Sub-band CQI value for each codeword. In this case both CQI values shall be added to the counter and are counted as two samples.

column16: The total number of E-RAB Releases per cell initiated by the MME excluding successful handover. The counter is stepped regardless of whether data was or was not lost in UL/DL buffers.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The counter is stepped for each released E-RAB at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command (except if the cause was successful handover) and with the pre-condition that the Initial Context Establishment procedure must first have been successfully completed. The release must also have been MME initiated.

column16: Total number of abnormal UE Context Releases for each cell initiated by the eNodeB, and the UE is in Out-of-Sync mode.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17:
Stepped if the UE is in Out-of-Sync state and at:
- Reception of UE Context Release Command when the release is initiated by the RBS and the internal cause code is considered as abnormal
- Transmission of UE Context Release Request or UE Context Release Request by the RBS
- Internal RBS UE Context Release due to disabling of a cell owned by that RBS

column16:
Total number of normal E-RAB release per cell per QCI. Bearer release is initiated by MME with normal release cause via S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command proceeded by inactivity longer than a configurable threshold in DL direction.

Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17:
Corresponding QCI bin is stepped by one for each released E-RAB when:
 - Inactive seconds before release greater than predefined threshold on DL.

column16:

If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer

column16:

Includes only bursts that start when the UE is in DRX Active state and UL In-sync state.\n\nEach bin accumulates latency for all DRBs with the corresponding QCI value. column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16:

column16: The counter counts the number of times a HARQ-process for random access message 4 fails for cases where the contention resolution counter has not expired. column17: The counter is stepped when the time of the transmit of the last HARQ transmission is within the contention resolution timer. Only a message 4 that contains a contention resolution identifier and that contains an RRC connection setup or an RRC connection re-establishment is counted.

column16:

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16:
Peak number of bandwidth reduced UEs considered active in the UL direction, per PRACH Coverage Enhancement (CE) level. A UE is considered active if it has data in its buffer. [0]: CE level 0
[1]: CE level 1
[2]: CE level 2
[3]: CE level 3

column16:
Number of GBR E-RAB Releases initiated by the MME considered as abnormal within this cell, recorded per ARP priority level. The counter is stepped if there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (that is active).

If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column16:
Aggregated DL Latency when DRX is active and the UE has UL synchronization status \synchronized".

When carrier aggregation is used, the DL Latency for all component carriers is registered on the UE's primary component carrier (PCell).
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner"
column17: The effective DL Latency time comprises the time from PDCP DRB SDU entering the buffer until the first data has been transmitted to the UE. Measurement for UEs aggregated to cell level. Only PDCP SDUs that enters an empty buffer are measured. Samples during handover are excluded since they can distort the interpretation of the result (due to packet forwarding, the target cell might have to buffer data before it is possible to schedule the UE in the target cell, hence it would be an increased Latency measurement if it would be included. It would however not lead to a degraded performance for the end-user, due to packet forwarding).

In the UL case, when a UE has multiple bearers coexisting and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. column16: The total number of abnormal E-RAB Releases per cell initiated by the eNB and that there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active).\nScanner: Primary
column17: If there was data in the buffer at the time of release, then stepped at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command when internal cause codes considered abnormal (Radio Connection with UE is lost; Handover failure for the UE; Non admitted E-RABs by target cell at successful handover for the UE; UE pre-emption) when the RBS initiated the release. It can also be stepped at transmission of E-RAB Release Indication, UE Context Release Request or Reset message by the RBS, or when a cell owned by that RBS is disabled (and that leads to internal RBS UE Context Release). In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.\nNote. When the release cause indicates partial node restart, the actual status of the buffer is indeterminate at time of the restart therefore the bearer is instead considered active based on the latest RBS internal activity information (typically 1 second resolution), meaning that a bearer counted as \active\" could have been inactive for up to 1 second."

column16: The number of detected contention-based random access preambles from non-bandwidth-reduced UEs.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16:

column16: Number of UE Context Fetch Request messages received during SRVCC handover to UTRAN execution.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

When carrier aggregation is used, a PDCP SDU can be sent over multiple cells (PCell/SCell(s)). The total number of bits (PDCP SDU) on Signalling Radio Bearers that has been transferred (acknowledged by the UE) in the downlink direction is measured on PCell.

column16:

- Transmission of UE Context Release Request or UE Context Release Request by the RBS

column16: The number of successful outgoing intra LTE inter frequency handovers that was performed due to MBMS Interest.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

UE CONTEXT RELEASE COMMAND received in the source eNodeB from the MME with the cause Handover Triggered (S1 handover) and the source eNB initiated the handover due MBMS Interest.
or
UE CONTEXT RELEASE received in the source eNodeB from the target eNodeB (X2 handover) and the source eNB initiated the handover due MBMS Interest.
or
Internal eNodeB trigger (corresponding to UE CONTEXT RELEASE) received when the UE has changed cell during an intra eNodeB handover and the source cell initiated the handover due MBMS Interest.

column17: Stepped if the UE is a PFT user in Out-of-Sync state, has data in any of its buffers and the E-RAB release is due to lost radio connection with the UE.

column16: Number of times a frequency is prioritized as target for cell reselection during idle mode at high load.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped every time priority of a frequency is raised in IdleModeMobilityControlInformation of message RrcConnectionRelease for load-balancing reasons when load is high.

column16:
Peak number of bandwidth reduced UEs considered active in the DL direction, per PRACH Coverage Enhancement (CE) level. A UE is considered active if it has designated data in its dedicated buffer in the eNB. The value is a maximum of a set of samples, where each sample is an average of active UEs per ms (throughout the frame), during a sample period shorter than the ROP.

PDF ranges:
[0]: CE level 0
[1]: CE level 1
[2]: CE level 2
[3]: CE level 3

Deprecated: Since 17.Q3. Replaced by pmActiveUeDlCe0Max, pmActiveUeDlCe1Max, pmActiveUeDlCe2Max and pmActiveUeDlCe3Max. Planned to be removed.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The counter is set equal to the peak sample recognized at the end of each Recording Output Period (ROP).

column16:
Total number of abnormal E-RAB releases by eNodeB for each cell due to:
 - cell down time (initiated automatically) caused by a partial node restart or
 - automated UE recovery.
Precondition: Initial Context Establishment procedure must first be successfully completed and that there is data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active).
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped for each E-RAB that is released due to cell down time (initiated automatically) caused by a partial node restart or due to automated UE recovery when data was in either the UL or DL buffer. In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

column16: Total number of measurement reports for Downlink Coordinated Multi-Point discarded by Layer 3.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when a measurement report for Downlink Coordinated Multi-Point event A5 is discarded by Layer 3 due to high MP load or if the measurement report does not include valid neighbor cells information.

column16:
Number of abnormal E-RAB Releases initiated by the MME within this cell, recorded per ARP priority level.

PDF ranges:
[0]: N/A (invalid ARP priority level value)
[1]: Number of recorded events for ARP priority level 1
...
[15]: Number of recorded events for ARP priority level 15

Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The bin for the corresponding ARP priority level is stepped for GBR E-RABs at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command with none of the causes Normal Release, Detach, CS Fallback Triggered or Redirection towards 1xRTT regardless if there was data in the UL or DL buffer. The release must also have been MME initiated.

column16: The total number of occasions when a downlink HARQ feedback for a transport block using 64QAM modulation was not received from an UE and DTX is considered the reason.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: To decide if it was DTX is based on not receiving any HARQ feedback on a transport block sent using 64QAM modulation.

column16:
Total number of normal E-RAB release per cell per QCI. Bearer release is initiated by MME with normal release cause via S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command proceeded by inactivity longer than a configurable threshold in UL direction.

Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17:
Corresponding QCI bin is stepped by one for each released E-RAB when:
 - Inactive seconds before release greater than predefined threshold on UL.
 - Initial Context Establishment procedure is first successfully completed.
 - MME-initiated normal releases only.

column16: The total number of successful S1 signaling connection establishments with Establishment cause Mobile Originating Data.\nScanner: Primary
column17: Stepped at first message received on this UE-associated logical S1-connection, if the RRC Connection Request Establishment cause was Establishment cause Mobile Originating Data.

column16:

column16:
DL transfer time, measured in ms, when MAC layer transmission in DL is needed on at least one DRB for the UE. This includes buffer waiting times and possible HARQ retransmission delays.
When carrier aggregation is used, a PDCP SDU can be transmitted over multiple cells, PCell or SCells. DL MAC transfer time over all carriers is incremented once on the PCell. This is suitable for PDCP timebase.
Unit: ms
Scanner: Primary
column17: Counts time when data arrives to at least one PDCP SDU buffer until all PDCP buffers and MAC HARQ buffers for the UE are emptied. This occurs by successful transmission or HARQ failure.\n\nContinuous measurement for each UE, accumulated to PCell level.

column16:
Total number of abnormal UE context releases by eNodeB due to:

 - automated UE recovery.
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
