column16: The total number of normal UE Context Releases triggered by RBS and that there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active).\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: If there was data in the buffer at the time of release, then stepped at reception of S1 message UE Context Release Command when internal cause codes considered normal (Successful Handover, User Inactivity, Inter-RAT redirection, CS Fallback Triggered) when the RBS initiated the release.

column16: The total number of abnormal E-RAB releases by eNodeB for each cell for each QCI due to handover preparation.\nCompressed: true.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: Total number of abnormal UE Context releases initiated by the eNodeB due to lost radio connection with the UE. The UE is a PFT UE and it is in Out-Of-Sync mode.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: Number of UE Context Fetch Request messages received during S1 handover execution.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

Samples summed over the measurement period. One sample per UE aperiodic rank 1 CQI report.

Valid UE reported CQI values range from 0 to 15

column16:

column16: Total number of measurement reports received from the UE.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column17:
One throughput sample is computed for each UE over each 1 second period. The histogram contains the samples from all UEs in the cell during the ROP.

The volume used for the throughput sample is the transmitted MAC volume on all DRBs for the UE.

The active time used for the throughput sample is number of ms in which there is need for MAC layer transmission in DL on at least one DRB for the UE. This includes buffer waiting times and possible HARQ retransmission delays.

column16: Successfully transferred data volume on MAC level in the downlink. This counter includes possible padding bits. Bandwidth-reduced UEs are excluded from this measurement.\nUnit: kilobit (1 000 bits)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: The number of complete HARQ failures. When a HARQ transmission has reached maximum number of retransmissions, it will not be retransmitted again and is regarded as a scheduling activity complete HARQ failure.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Increment at each scheduling activity complete harq failure.

column16: Number of times pmRrcConnCeCellLevSum has accumulated new samples for all PRACH Coverage Enhancement (CE) levels. Associated ACC pmCounter pmRrcConnCeCellLevSum.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: Maximum utilization of CQI resources in the long resource pool.\nUnit: %\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: The accumulated interference power for PRB53\nUnit: mW * 2^(-44)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: Total number of UL packets (PDCP SDUs) received per QCI.\nCompressed: True\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The bin accumulates the number of UL PDCP SDUs that are successfully received per QCI.

column16: The accumulated interference power for PRB59\nUnit: mW * 2^(-44)\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Samples summed over the measurement period. Measurements are averaged over receive antennas. One sample for each PRB per 40ms.

DL assignments for message 2 and broadcast messages are excluded.\nThe counter is pegged when licenses for both CarrierAggregation and EnhancedPdcchLa are enabled, and CarrierAggregation feature is activated.

column16: The total number of users scheduled per PRB pair. Incremented for PRB pairs used for Dedicated Traffic Channel (DTCH) transmissions on the Physical Downlink Shared Channel (PDSCH) only.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: The number of allocated CFRA preambles.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16:

Stepped in case UE type is Tune-out

column16: The total number of E-RAB Releases per cell, initiated by the MME with the pre-condition that the Initial Context Establishment procedure must first have been successfully completed and that there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active) and the cause was \Unspecified\".\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner"

In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter  is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer."

column10: Contains all PM counters for NodeBLocalCellGroup
column16:
Distribution of the UL channel (DPCCH) activity factor for CPC activated E-DCH connections, as a percentage of time. This counter gives, on a per connection basis, the ratio between the number of slots where the UL DPCCH is transmitted and the total number of slots during the connection. The counter accumulates all CPC users.
Bins:
[0]: Number of samples in range [0..5[ %
[1]: Number of samples in range [5..10[ %
...
[18]: Number of samples in range [90..95[ %
[19]: Number of samples in range [95..100] %
column17: \nActivity factor (%) is computed by dividing number of slots for which uplink DPCCH was received by total number of uplink DPCCH slots in considered time frame. Measurement starts when EUL resources are setup with CPC activated and ends at the end of the connection. Activity factor is calculated once for each user and fed into appropriate PDF bin.\n

column16: The number of IP packets that have matched the ACL entry.
column17: Incremented each time an IP packet has been evaluated against the corresponding ACL Entry and the evaluation resulted in a match.

column16: Number of users where co-reception is complete in cooperating BBM. Handled by cooperating BBM.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when cooperating BBM sends inter-eNodeB UL CoMP response to serving BBM.

column16: Number of users included in inter-eNodeB UL CoMP request from serving BBM. Handled by cooperating BBM.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when cooperating BBM receives inter-eNodeB UL CoMP request.

column16: Number of users received from inter-enodeB UL response in serving BBM. Handled by serving BBM.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when serving BBM receives inter-eNodeB UL CoMP response.

column16: Number of users that request co-reception in serving BBM. Handled by serving BBM.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when serving BBM sends inter-eNodeB UL CoMP request.

column16: The number of received SCTP datagrams for which an SCTP association could not be determined.
column17: An SCTP datagram is received, but is not delivered due to inability to find the association and endpoint.

column16: Number of times that SCTP associations have made a direct transition to the ESTABLISHED state from the COOKIE-ECHOED state.
column17: State change from COOKIE-ECHOED directly to ESTABLISHED.

column16: Number of times that SCTP associations have made a direct transition from the CLOSED state to the ESTABLISHED state
column17: State change from CLOSED directly to ESTABLISHED.

column16: Number of transmitted control chunks.
column17: A control chunk is transmitted.

column16: Number of received control chunks. The counter does not include abnormal or discarded chunks.
column17: A control chunk is received.

column16: Number of reassembled user messages, incremented when the first data chunk of a fragmented message is received.
column17: The first data chunk of a fragmented message is received.

column16: Number of transmitted ordered DATA chunks (excluding retransmissions).
column17: A DATA chunk is transmitted.

column16: Number of transmitted packets.
column17: An SCTP package is transmitted.

column16: Number of times that SCTP associations have made a direct transition to the CLOSED state from any state, using the chunk ABORT.
column17: Number of retransmitted DATA chunks.

column16: Number of unordered chunks transmitted to the peers.
column17: An unordered chunk is transmitted.

column16: Number of DATA chunks retransmitted to the peers.
column17: A DATA chunk is retransmitted.

column16: Number of fragmented user messages, incremented when the first data chunk of fragmented message is sent.
column17: A fragmented message is transmitted.

column16: Number of SCTP packets received from the peers, with an invalid checksum.
column17: An SCTP packet with invalid checksum received.

column16: Number of received ordered DATA chunks.\n\nThe counter does NOT include abnormal or discarded chunks.
column17: A DATA chunk is received.

column16: Number of unordered chunks received from the peers.
column17: An unordered chunk is received.

column16: Number of times SCTP has sent a congestion indication to the user.
column17: A communication stop indication is sent.

column16:
Number of received chunks dropped for the following reasons: 
- Invalid association state
- Duplicated data
- Invalid stream identity in the DATA_CHUNK
- Invalid verification tag in the packet
- Stale SACK_CHUNK received
- Lack of receiving buffer
- ULP buffer overflow.
column17: A received chunk is discarded.

column16: Number of received packets, including duplicates and those received in error.
column17: A SCTP package is received.

column16: Number of out-of-the-blue packets that are received by the host.\n\nThese are SCTP packets that are correctly formed (with a correct checksum), but where the receiver is not able to identify the association to which this packet belongs.
column17: An unidentified packet is received.

column16: The number of received SCTP datagrams for which an SCTP association and endpoint could not be determined (for example if there was no user application at the destination port).
column17: An SCTP datagram is received, but is not delivered due to inability to find the association and endpoint.

column16: Number of outgoing user messages originating from the application for this SCTP for which no problems were encountered to prevent their transmission but were discarded. User messages are discarded due to lack of thrTransmitBuffer.
column17: A sent user message is discarded.

column16: Number of times that SCTP associations have made a direct transition to the CLOSED state from either the SHUTDOWN-SENT state or the SHUTDOWN-ACK-SENT state.
column17: State change from SHUTDOWN-SENT or SHUTDOWN-ACK-SENT directly to CLOSED.

column16: Number of times SCTP has sent a congestion ceased indication to the user.
column17: A communication resume indication is sent.

column16: The number of packets that have been discarded due to matching an ACL Entry with action \Deny\", or not matching any ACL Entry."
column17: Incremented each time an IP packet has been discarded due to a \Deny\" action in this ACL, including the default implicit \"Deny\"."

column16: With Elastic RAN UL CoMP activated, number of valid requested Comp UE in cooperating eNodeB. MEAS UE not included.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when cooperating cell receiving UL COMP request.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
Counts the number of TTIs where this partner was blocked by the node due to link delay and/or missed deadlines.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: With Elastic RAN UL CoMP activated, number of requested Comp UE in serving eNodeB. MEAS UE not included.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: Counts number of inter-eNB-CA-specific packets received but deemed to be too late to be usable and discarded. Pegged by scheduler on the external eNB.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Accumulates when the link is inter-eNB. This counter does not step for the Elastic RAN CA feature.

column16: With Elastic RAN UL CoMP activated, number of valid responded Comp UE in serving eNodeB. MEAS UE not included.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when serving cell receiving UL COMP response.

column16: With Elastic RAN UL CoMP activated, number of responded Comp UE in cooperating eNodeB. MEAS UE not included.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when cooperating cell sending UL COMP response.

column16: Counts each occurrence of CRNTI unavailability at the external eNodeB when configuration of ESCell takes place.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when a CRNTI is not available on the external eNodeB.

column16: Counts number of packets for CA lost due to detected errors such as sequence missing, packet header errors, etc.\nReported on receiving eNB.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Accumulates when the link is inter-eNB. This counter does not step for the Elastic RAN CA feature.

column16: Counts number of discarded CA packets, such as packets received out of order.\nReported on receiving eNB.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Accumulates when the link is Elastic RAN or inter-eNB.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

Counts number of packets transmitted by this eNB to another eNB for inter-nodal CA. Application data can be bidirectional.\nReported on transmitting eNB.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Accumulates when the link is Elastic RAN or inter-eNB.

column16: Counts number of packets successfully received by an eNB from another eNB for CA. Application data can be bidirectional.\nReported on receiving eNB.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Accumulates when the link is Elastic RAN or inter-eNB.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16:
Propagation delay between UEs and the antenna for a cell, as
percentage of the maximum propagation delay within the cell (indicated by the
counter pmPrachPropagationDelayMax).

Bins:
[0]: 0 (not used)
[1]: Number of samples less than 1 %
[2]: Number of samples in range [1..2[ %
...
[10]: Number of samples in range [9..10[ %
[11]: Number of samples in range [10..12[ %
[12]: Number of samples in range [12..14[ %
...
[20]: Number of samples in range [28..30[ %
[21]: Number of samples in range [30..33[ %
[22]: Number of samples in range [33..36[ %
...
[30]: Number of samples in range [57..60[ %
[31]: Number of samples in range [60..64[ %
[32]: Number of samples in range [64..68[ %
...
[40]: Number of samples greater than or equal to 96 %
column17: Measurement is started when the PRACH is setup. Propagation delay is measured on RACH messages with correct CRC. A sample is taken from each detected preamble with successful detected message. Note that if the propagation delay of a RACH message with correct CRC is negative, bin 1 is incremented, and If the propagation delay of a RACH message with correct CRC is larger than the cell range, bin 40 is incremented. The counter is not stepped due to EUL FACH activity.

[2]: Number of sampled values in range [-24..-23[ dB
...
[25]: Number of sampled values in range [-1..0[ dB
[26]: Number of sampled values greater than or equal to 0
column17: The actual measurement is started when the PRACH is setup. The counter is not stepped due to EUL FACH activity.

column16: Measured temperature for the SFP. Unit: 1 degree C. Deprecated since 16B. Moved to SfpModule.

column16: The total number of Loss of Frame (LOF) errors detected on the port. Only valid for C1 (CPRI) link.
column17: Number of detected Loss of Frame related errors are accumulated within the granularity period. This can include errors which did not result in an alarm being raised. Recorded events are accumulated every 60 seconds.

column16: Measured RX output power for the SFP. Unit: 0.01 dBm. Value is reported with offset of +3000. To convert to dBm value use the formula dBm = ((value_reported - 3000)/100). For example, a reported value of 602 represents -23.98dBm. Deprecated since 16B. Moved to SfpModule.
column17: Reports the last measured RX output power on the SFP within the granularity period. A sample is taken every 900 seconds

column16: Measured TX bias current for the SFP. Unit: 1 mA. Deprecated since 16B. Moved to SfpModule.

column16: The total number of Loss of Signal (LOS) errors detected on the port.
column17: Number of detected Loss of Signal related errors are accumulated within the granularity period. This can include errors which did not result in an alarm being raised. Recorded events are accumulated every 60 seconds.

column16: Estimated bit error rate on the port. PDF ranges: [0]: Number of samples with bit error rate 10^-8 [1]: Number of samples with bit error rate 10^-7 [2]: Number of samples with bit error rate 10^-6 [3]: Number of samples with bit error rate 10^-5 [4]: Number of samples with bit error rate 10^-4 [5]: Number of samples with bit error rate 10^-3
column17: Counts number of line code violations during 1 sec, divided by total number of symbols or blocks. Estimated BER level increments corresponding counter.

column16: Measured TX output power for the SFP. Unit: 0.01 dBm. Value is reported with offset of +3000. To convert to dBm value use the formula dBm = ((value_reported - 3000)/100). For example, a reported value of 602 represents -23.98dBm. Deprecated since 16B. Moved to SfpModule.
column17: Reports the last measured TX output power on the SFP within the granularity period. A sample is taken every 900 seconds

column16: Measured voltage for the SFP. Unit: 1 degree V. Deprecated since 16B. Moved to SfpModule.

column16: This counter specifies the current footprint in the eNB from the configured MO instances for all different Cell Relations and External Cells in relation to the MO system limit. column16: The number of packets received via the interface which were discarded because of an unknown or unsupported protocol. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6. Unit: Packets

The number of outbound packets which were discarded even though no errors had been detected, for example due to lack of buffer space or traffic shaping. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6. Unit: Packets
The total number of broadcast packets that are requested to be transmitted. Broadcast packets counted by ifOutDiscards are included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6. Unit: Packets
The total number of multicast packets that are requested to be transmitted. Multicast packets counted by ifOutDiscards are included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6. Unit: Packets
The total number of octets received on the interface, including framing characters. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6. Unit: Octets

The number of broadcast packets forwarded to a bridge or delivered to a higher (sub-)layer. Packets counted by ifInUnknownProtos are not included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6. Unit: Packets

The number of multicast packets forwarded to a bridge or delivered to a higher (sub-)layer. Packets counted by ifInUnknownProtos are not included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6. Unit: Packets
The total number of unicast packets that are requested to be transmitted. Unicast packets counted by ifOutDiscards are included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6. Unit: Packets
The total number of octets transmitted out of the interface, including framing characters. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6. Unit: Octets

The number of inbound packets which were chosen to be discarded even though no errors had been detected to prevent their being deliverable to a higher-layer protocol. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6.
The number of unicast packets forwarded to a bridge or delivered to a higher (sub-)layer. Packets counted by ifInUnknownProtos are not included. Standard reference: RFC 2863, section 6. Unit: Packets

Number of successful handovers that are:

column10: Contains all PM counters for GSM Sector.
column16: Power utilization statistics for all TX RF branches used by GSM sector.
column17:
Counts bursts with specific nominal power. 
				Bins: 
				[0]: Bursts with nominal power greater than 100% of reserved power available for GSM in GSM sector. 
				[1]: Bursts with nominal power less or equal to 100% and greater than 90% of reserved power available for GSM in GSM sector. 
				[2]: Bursts with nominal power less or equal to 90% and greater than 80% of reserved power available for GSM in GSM sector. 
				[3]: Bursts with nominal power less or equal to 80% and greater than 70% of reserved power available for GSM in GSM sector. 
				[4]: Bursts with nominal power less or equal to 70% and greater than 60% of reserved power available for GSM in GSM sector.
				[5]: Bursts with nominal power less or equal to 60% and greater than 50% of reserved power available for GSM in GSM sector. 
				[6]: Bursts with nominal power less or equal to 50% of reserved power available for GSM in GSM sector.

column10: Contains all PM counters for GSM Sector.
column16: Accumulated time in seconds when none of the TX connected to an MCPA indicates power. Measured for each MCPA in each radio in the GSM Sector, and summed up. This counter is part of feature Micro TX Sleep GSM, and indicates the total amount of time when power savings can be achieved with radios capable of Micro TX Sleep GSM.
column17: For shared radios, the counter adds up the micro sleep time in both Basebands/DUs even when one Baseband/DU indicates no power and the other indicates power. For TX Diversity the time is counted twice as Tx Diversity uses two TX bursts, one per MCPA. TX bursts for TRX in MCPA TX Power Saving mode are not counted as the TX is disabled. The counter is cleared at TX Reset.

column17: For TX Diversity the time is counted twice as TX Diversity uses two TX bursts, one per MCPA. TX bursts used on BCCH TRX are also counted even though BCCH TRX cannot micro sleep. TX bursts for TRX in MCPA Power saving mode are not counted as the TX is disabled. The counter is cleared at TX Reset.

column10: Contains all PM counters for EDchResources
column16:
Number of grant reductions made by EUL Scheduler due to different reasons.
Count for each reason is given by a separate bin.

Bins:
[0]: TN Congestion -- Incremented every time a grant reduction is triggered due to a TCI (TNL Congestion Indication) received by the scheduler.
[1]: Uu Congestion Serving -- Incremented every time an absolute grant overload action is taken due insufficient scheduling headroom.
[2]: Uu Congestion Non-serving -- Incremented every time a relative grant overload action is taken due insufficient scheduling headroom.
[3]: HW Congestion -- Incremented every time an overload action is taken due insufficient UL HW.
[4]: Low usage happy -- Incremented every time a happy user's grant is reduced due to consistently low usage of the granted rate.
[5]: Low usage unhappy -- Incremented every time an unhappy user's grant is reduced due to consistently low usage of the granted rate.
[6]: Not used -- Always reported as 0.
[7]: Inactivity at high grant -- Incremented when a user with a high grant is reduced to the minimum UL HW allocation due to data inactivity on the UL.
[8]: Rescheduling -- Incremented every time a user's rate is reduced due to rescheduling in the scheduler.
column17: The actual measurement is started when the EUL resources are setup. The counter is not stepped due to EUL FACH activity.\n

column17: RRC CONNECTION RECONFIGURATION including the mobilityControlInformation is sent to the UE from the source cell due to non-mobility reasons

column16: Number of UEs that report the related UTRAN cell as the strongest cell in connection with measurements initiated for Admission-Triggered Offload.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when a UE reports the related UTRAN cell as the strongest cell.

column16: Number of successful handovers to UTRAN or TD-SCDMA.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: UE CONTEXT RELEASE COMMAND received in the source eNodeB from the MME with the cause Handover Triggered (S1 handover) .

column16: Number of successful SRVCC handovers to UTRAN caused by load balancing action.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Command UE CONTEXT RELEASE received in the source eNodeB steps the counter. The command comes from the MME, where load balancing causes S1 Handover Triggered including a VoIP bearer.

column16: Number of successful SRVCC handover to UTRAN preparations due to load balancing action\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The HANDOVER COMMAND message is received from the MME (S1 handover) and the eNodeB initiated the handover due to load balancing action and SRVCC handover is required.

column16: The number of handover execution attempts triggered by CS Fallback Emergency Call.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: MobilityFromEUTRACommand with target RAT information is sent to the UE when CS Fallback Emergency Call is initiated for the UE to a WCDMA cell.

column16: Number of execution attempts caused by load-balancing action. Part of the total of SRVCC handover to UTRAN execution attempts.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Load balancing triggers command MobilityFromEUTRACommand towards the UTRAN cell including a VoIP bearer.

column16: Number of UEs that report the related UTRAN cell as the strongest cell in connection with measurements initiated for load balancing or offload.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when UE reports related UTRAN cell as strongest cell.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
The number of successful handovers triggered by CS Fallback Emergency Call to the selected cell.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: UE CONTEXT RELEASE COMMAND that indicates successful handover to a WCDMA cell when CS Fallback Emergency Call is initiated for the UE.

column10: Contains all PM counters for RadioLinks
column16: Number of times RLSs, within the related local cell, go from state synchronized to unsynchronized.
column17: Measurement starts when MO RadioLinks is created. Each state change from synchronized to unsyncronized increases the counter by 1. The counter is not stepped for EUL FACH activity.

column10: Contains all PM counters for RadioLinks
column16: Average transmitted code power on a DPCH channel for spreading factor 8 for small cells (with low output power).
column17:
Transmitted code power measurement starts when MO RadioLinks is created. One measurement for each RLS or at RL addition owing to inter-frequency handover.
Transmitted power is measured in dBm on each chip of the DPCH pilot bits. Average values calculated every 100 ms and stored in applicable counters, depending on SF. Power values are sorted to the RL normal mode spreading factor (SF 8). Also true when power values originate from radio frames with spreading factor halved because of compressed mode method SF/2. If two branches are used, then the sum is used for calculations.
Counter is limited to one set of measurements for each RL and to measuring a maximum of 10% of CE capacity for each local cell group.

Bins:
[0]: number of sampled values less than -15 dbm
[1]: Number of sampled values in range [-15..-14[ dBm
...
[37]: Number of sampled values in range [21..22] dBm

column10: Contains all PM counters for RadioLinks
column16:

[1]: Number of sampled values in range [-7..-6.5[ dB
[2]: Number of sampled values in range [-6.5..-6[ dB

column16: The number (64-bit) of octets transmitted into the queue. Ethernet header, payload and FCS are counted. Unit: Octets
column17: Increases if octet transmitted into the RED queue

column16: The number (64-bit) of samples, taken a 1000 times per ROP, when a queue is filled more than 80% of its size.
column17: Increases if queue utilization is larger than 80%.

column16: The number (64-bit) of packets transmitted into the queue. Unit: Packets
column17: Increases if packet transmitted into the RED queue

column16: The number (64-bit) of samples, taken a 1000 times per ROP, when a queue is filled more than 20% of its size.
column17: Increases if queue utilization is larger than 20%.

column16: The number (64-bit) of packets transmitted by the queue. Ethernet header, payload and FCS are counted. Unit: Octets
column17: Increases if packets sent by RED

column16: The number (64-bit) of packets discarded by the queue. Unit: Packets
column17: Increases if packet dropped by RED

column16: The number (64-bit) of octets transmitted by the queue. Ethernet header, payload and FCS are counted. Unit: Octets
column17: Increases if octet sent by RED

column16: The number (64-bit) of octets discarded by the queue. Ethernet header, payload and FCS are counted. Unit: Octets
column17: Increases if octet dropped by RED

column16: The number of input IP datagrams discarded due to errors in  their IP headers, including version number mismatch, other  format errors, hop count exceeded, errors discovered in  processing their IP options, etc. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of output IP datagrams for which no problem was encountered to prevent their transmission to their destination, but were discarded (e.g., for lack of buffer space). Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The total number of IP datagrams that this entity supplied to the lower layers for transmission. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of failures detected by the IP re-assembly algorithm. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of IP broadcast datagrams transmitted. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of IP fragments received that needed to be reassembled at this interface. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of output datagram fragments that have been generated as a result of IP fragmentation. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of input datagrams for which this entity was not  their final IP destination and for which this entity attempted to find a route to forward them to that final destination. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The total number of octets received in input IP datagrams, including those received in error. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of packets that were forwarded to a null route. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set.
The total number of octets received in IP multicast datagrams. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of input IP datagrams discarded because the datagram frame didn't carry enough data. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of input IP datagrams that are discarded, because no route could be found to transmit them to their destination. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of IP datagrams that have been discarded because they needed to be fragmented but could not be. This includes IPv4 packets that have the DF bit set. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of IP multicast datagrams transmitted. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of IP datagrams successfully reassembled. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
Distribution of the egress throughput on the IPv4 interface measured in octets per second.\nThe throughput samples are based on ipIfStatsHCOutOctets and are taken every second.
column17: Each bin is calculated as a percentile value at the end of the ROP period. 7 percentile values are presented in the bins [0,1,...,6] = [P0, P95, P96, P97, P98, P99, P100].

column16: The number of IP multicast datagrams received. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The total number of IP datagrams that local IP user-protocols (including ICMP) supplied to IP in requests for transmission. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of IP datagrams that have been successfully fragmented. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The total number of octets in IP datagrams delivered to the lower layers for transmission. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of IP datagrams that would require fragmentation in order to be transmitted. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The total number of datagrams successfully delivered to IP user-protocols (including ICMP). Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of input IP datagrams discarded because the IP address in their IP header's destination field was not a valid address to be received at this entity. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The number of IP broadcast datagrams received. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
Distribution of the ingress throughput on the IPv4 interface measured in octets per second.\nThe throughput samples are based on ipIfStatsHCInOctets and are taken every second.
column17: Each bin is calculated as a percentile value at the end of the ROP period. 7 percentile values are presented in the bins [0,1,...,6] = [P0, P95, P96, P97, P98, P99, P100].

column16: The number of input IP datagrams for which no problems were  encountered to prevent their continued processing, but were discarded (e.g., for lack of buffer space). Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of input IP datagrams discarded because the IP address in their IP header's source field was not a valid address to be received at this entity. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set.

The total number of input IP datagrams received, including those received in error. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.
The total number of octets transmitted in IP multicast datagrams. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of datagrams for which this entity was not their final IP destination and for which it was successful in finding a path to their final destination. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

The number of locally-addressed IP datagrams received successfully but discarded because of an unknown or unsupported protocol. Not applicable for an IP Loopback Interface, that is, if the attribute loopback is set. Specification: RFC 4293, section 5.

column16:
Abnormal E-RAB Releases initiated by RBS (per cell per ARP).Stepped if data was present in UL or DL buffers.

PDF ranges:
[0]: Sum of active E-RABs released with ARP priority value 0
[1]: Sum of active E-RABs released with ARP priority value 1
....
[15]: Sum of active E-RABs released with ARP priority value 15
Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: If there was data in the buffer at the time of release, then stepped at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command, for E-RAB/s with the specific ARP Priority Level, when internal cause codes considered abnormal (Radio Connection with UE is lost; Handover failure for the UE; Non admitted E-RABs by target cell at successful handover for the UE; UE pre-emption; Bearer pre-emption) when the RBS initiated the release. It can also be stepped at transmission of Reset message by the RBS, or when a cell owned by that RBS is disabled (and that leads to internal RBS UE Context Release). In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.\nNote. When the release cause indicates partial node restart, the actual status of the buffer is indeterminate at time of the restart therefore the bearer is instead considered active based on the latest RBS internal activity information (typically 1 second resolution), meaning that a bearer counted as \active\" could have been inactive for up to 1 second."

column16: The number of successfully completed CFRA procedures. Measured when first UL-SCH message is received after detection of the CFRA preamble.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: The total number of successful HARQ transmissions in the downlink direction where a dSINR from DL CoMP was applied in the Link Adaptation.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Counter should be incremented every successful HARQ transmissions in the downlink direction where a dSINR from DL CoMP was applied in the Link Adaptation.

column16: The total number of normal UE Context Releases triggered by RBS. The counter is stepped regardless of whether data was or was not lost in UL/DL buffers.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: The total number of abnormal UE Context releases by the eNB due to that the radio connection with the UE is lost.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: The number of CBRA preambles that are discarded because timing offset of CBRA preamble corresponds to a distance greater than configured cell range.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: Number of times corresponding Sum counter accumulates new samples. Associated ACC pmCounter pmRrcConnNs05RepeaterZoneSum.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: Stepped when corresponding sum counter has accumulated a new sample.

column16: Normally this counter is not used, it can however sometimes be temporarily used for very late additions in a release. If so, for description see Network Impact Report in the CPI.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16:

column16: Number of RRC Connection Re-establishment attempts differentiated for each QCI. Counter is only stepped if Context Fetch procedure is successful.\nCompressed: True\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16:

column16: Number of times a frequency is prioritized as target for cell reselection during idle mode at low load.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16:
The DL MAC latency time for data bursts that arrive when the UE is in DRX inactivity period and in UL Out-of-sync state. It is accumulated over all DRBs with QCIs in the given range.

The range of the QCIs included into the measurement is given by the MOM parameters minQciLatencyMeas and maxQciLatencyMeas.

column17: Counts time from when the data arrives to the empty PDCP SDU buffer while MAC DRB buffer is also empty, until the first data on the MAC layer is transmitted. Includes only bursts when the UE is in DRX inactivity period and UL Out-of-sync state.\n\nContinuous measurement for each DRB with the QCI in the range, on each UE, aggregated to cell level.

column16:
The number of successful E-RAB Modify attempts per QCI.
Note: since the QCI itself can be modified, if an E-RAB on QCI x is modified to QCI y, bin [x] would be used (and for subsequent E-RAB Modify attempts, bin [y] would be used).

Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

The counter is stepped periodically at each measurement interval of CCE utilization level for each cell.

column16:

Compressed: True
Scanner: Not included in any predefined scanner
column17: The bin accumulates the number of DL PDCP SDUs that are not successfully transmitted due to reasons other than HO per QCI.

column16: Counts the number of times the corresponding Sum counters has been incremented.\nAssociated ACC pmCounter pmErabLevSum.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: The total number of abnormal UE Contexts Releases initiated by the RBS due to license reject.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

Continuous measurement for each DRB aggregated to cell level.

column16: Number of DRB packets for downlink Latency measurements.\nScanner: Primary
column17: Measurement for UEs aggregated to cell level. Only PDCP SDUs that enters an empty buffer are measured. Samples during handover are excluded since they can distort the interpretation of the result (due to packet forwarding, the target cell might have to buffer data before it is possible to schedule the UE in the target cell, hence it would be an increased Latency measurement if it would be included. It would however not lead to a degraded performance for the end-user, due to packet forwarding).

column16: The number of RRC Connection Release with redirect to TD-SCDMA triggered by CS Fallback Emergency.\nScanner: Primary

column16: New unicast DL assignments sent during DRX onDuration and confirmed by corresponding HARQ ACK/NACK.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

column16: The total number of abnormal E-RAB Releases per cell initiated by the eNB and that there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active).\nScanner: Primary
column17: If there was data in the buffer at the time of release, then stepped at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command when internal cause codes considered abnormal (Radio Connection with UE is lost; Handover failure for the UE; Non admitted E-RABs by target cell at successful handover for the UE; UE pre-emption) when the RBS initiated the release. It can also be stepped at transmission of E-RAB Release Indication, UE Context Release Request or Reset message by the RBS, or when a cell owned by that RBS is disabled (and that leads to internal RBS UE Context Release). In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.\nNote. When the release cause indicates partial node restart, the actual status of the buffer is indeterminate at time of the restart therefore the bearer is instead considered active based on the latest RBS internal activity information (typically 1 second resolution), meaning that a bearer counted as \active\" could have been inactive for up to 1 second."

column16: The total number of E-RAB Releases per cell, initiated by the MME with the pre-condition that the Initial Context Establishment procedure must first have been successfully completed and that there was data in either the UL or DL buffer (i.e. active) and the cause was \User Inactivity\".\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner"

One throughput sample is computed for each UE over each 1 second period. The histogram contains the samples from all UEs in the cell during the ROP.

The volume used for the throughput sample is the transmitted MAC volume on all DRBs for the UE.

column16: Aggregated DL Latency for a measurement period. The effective DL Latency time comprises the time from PDCP DRB SDU entering the buffer until the first data has been transmitted to the UE.\nUnit: ms\nScanner: Primary
column17: Measurement for UEs aggregated to cell level. Only PDCP SDUs that enters an empty buffer are measured. Samples during handover are excluded since they can distort the interpretation of the result (due to packet forwarding, the target cell might have to buffer data before it is possible to schedule the UE in the target cell, hence it would be an increased Latency measurement if it would be included. It would however not lead to a degraded performance for the end-user, due to packet forwarding).

column16: Number of DRB packets (PDCP SDUs) discarded in the downlink due to handover and reestablishment procedures.\nScanner: Not included in any predefined scanner

Discards in the source eNB includes discards of PDCP SDU packets not positively acknowledged for which it was decided that no more transmission attempts on either Uu, X2 or S1 interface will be done. In the reestablishment functionality, packets in the PDCP buffer are discarded due to the reestablishment procedure. Only applicable to DRB packets.

column16:
Delay distribution between reception of random access message 3 and successful transmission of random access message 4. Only counts message 4s that contain a contention resolution identity and no RRC message or a contention resolution identity and an RRC connection reject or an RRC connection re-establishment reject message.

PDF ranges:
[0]: less than or equals to 8 ms
[1]: ]8..16] ms
[2]: ]16..24] ms
[3]: ]24..32] ms
[4]: ]32..40] ms
[5]: ]40..48] ms
[6]: ]48..56] ms
[7]: ]56..64] ms
[8]: greater than 64 ms

column17: The counter is stepped when the eNB has received a positive acknowledgement of a random access message 4 from the UE. The delay is measured from the reception of the message 3 to the transmission of the message 4. Only a message 4 that contains a contention resolution identifier and no RRC message or that contains a contention resolution identifier and an RRC connection reject or an RRC connection re-establishment reject is counted.

column16:

If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the associated counter for the bearer is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.

[1]: Number of recorded events for ARP priority level 1
...

column17: If there was data in the buffer at the time of release of a GBR E-RAB, then the bin for the corresponding ARP priority level is stepped at reception of S1 message E-RAB Release Command or UE Context Release Command when internal cause codes considered abnormal (Radio Connection with UE is lost; Handover failure for the UE; Non admitted E-RABs by target cell at successful handover for the UE; UE pre-emption; Bearer pre-emption) when the RBS initiated the release. It can also be stepped at transmission of Reset message by the RBS, or when a cell owned by that RBS is disabled (and that leads to internal RBS UE Context Release). In the UL case when a UE has multiple bearers co-existing and sharing the same LCG, the bearers share a single packet queue. If one of the bearers is released and there is data in the queue, the bearer's associated counter is incremented, regardless of whether or not the data belongs to the released bearer.\nNote: When the release cause indicates partial node restart, the actual status of the buffer is indeterminate at time of the restart therefore the bearer is instead considered active based on the latest RBS internal activity information (typically 1 second resolution), meaning that a bearer counted as \active\" could have been inactive for up to 1 second."
